{"title_page": "Fikile Mbalula", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n|name               = Fikile Razzmatazz Mbalula\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|honorific-suffix   = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image              = CGF Durban2022Bid-7747 (Fikile Mbalula cropped).jpg\n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = \n|president          = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|office             = [[Minister of Transport (South Africa)|Minister of Transport]]\n|term_start         = 30 May 2019\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = [[Blade Nzimande]]\n|successor          = \n|office2            = [[Minister of Police (South Africa)|Minister of Police]]\n|president2         = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start2        = 31 March 2017\n|term_end2 = 26 February 2018\n|predecessor2       = [[Nkosinathi Nhleko]]\n|successor2         = [[Bheki Cele]]\n|office3            = [[Minister of Sport and Recreation (South Africa)|Minister of Sport and Recreation]]\n|president3         = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start3        = 1 November 2010\n|term_end3          = 31 March 2017\n|predecessor3       = [[Makhenkesi Stofile]]\n|successor3         = [[Thembelani Nxesi]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1991|04|08}}\n|birth_place        = [[Ngquza, Eastern Cape]]\n|death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place        = \n|birthname          = \n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = [[South African]]\n|party              = [[African National Congress]]\n|otherparty         = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = \n|partner            = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n}}\n'''Fikile April Mbalula''' (born 8 April 1971<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps.gcis.gov.za/gcis/gcis_profile.jsp?id=6397 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804235648/http://apps.gcis.gov.za/gcis/gcis_profile.jsp?id=6397 |archivedate=2012-08-04 }}</ref> in the [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]]) is a South African politician who is currently serving as Minister of Transport. He previously served as both [[Minister of Police (South Africa)|Minister and Deputy Minister of Police]] and Minister of Sports and Recreation. Mbalula is a member of the National Executive Committee of the [[African National Congress]] and former leader of the [[African National Congress Youth League]].\n\n==Career==\nMbalula was appointed Deputy Minister of Police in the cabinet of Jacob Zuma in May 2009 and later became the Minister of Sport and Recreation after President Jacob Zuma changed his cabinet. On 31 March 2017, following a controversial reshuffling in the cabinet, Mbalula was appointed as Minister of Police taking over from [[Nkosinathi Nhleko|Nathi Nhleko]] <ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/Elections/News/0,,2-2478-2479_2514142,00.html New Cabinet \u2013 full appointments] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512103024/http://www.news24.com/News24/Elections/News/0,,2-2478-2479_2514142,00.html |date=May 12, 2009 }} ''News24''</ref> after lobbying from the ANC Youth League<ref>[http://www.sowetan.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=995024 ANCYL wants its cadres in top posts]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Sowetan''</ref><ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2514063,00.html Speculation about Zuma's cabinet] ''News24''</ref> and possibly as a reward for loyalty towards Zuma,<ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/Elections/News/0,,2-2478-2479_2513057,00.html Zuma's Cabinet: Who's in?] ''News24''</ref> according to media speculation.\n\nIn the [[2009 South African general election|2009 general elections]] he was the manager of the ANC election campaign, which was considered highly successful.<ref>[http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/topstories.aspx?ID=BD4A987045 Slick party machinery wins the day] ''Business Day''</ref>\n\nMbalula was elected to the ANC NEC at the party's [[Polokwane]] conference in December 2007 in 15th place, measured in the number of votes.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=vn20071221112828576C498669 Meet Jacob Zuma's A-team] ''IOL''</ref> He subsequently retired as president of the ANC Youth League of which, at age 36, he was no longer eligible to be a member.<ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2180863,00.html ANCYL president to retire at 36] ''News24''</ref>\n\nMbalula was elected president of the ANC Youth League in August 2004, having previously held the post of secretary general.<ref>[http://www.sabcnews.com/politics/the_parties/0,2172,86282,00.html ANC Youth League calls on members to put country first] ''SABC''</ref>\n\nMbalula has been credited with installing South African President Thabo Mbeki in that position, and for later deposing him as head of the ANC.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=vn20080111073807686C336747 Zuma's NWC vs Mbeki's cabinet] ''Independent Online''</ref> His support has also been described as key in gaining Zuma the ANC presidency in a hard-fought race with Mbeki.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22952688-5003402,00.html Zuma backers urge new direction] ''News.com.au''</ref>\n\nHe also supported the candidacy of [[Julius Malema]] to succeed him as head of the Youth League in what was seen as a move to ensure continuing League support for Zuma.<ref>[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-04-07-malema-elected-as-new-ancyl-leader Malema elected as new ANCYL leader] ''Mail & Guardian''</ref>\n\nApart from politics, he is an ardent supporter of the [[Kaizer Chiefs Football Club]], and the \"Minister of Twitter\".\n\nIn May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] appointed Mbalula to the post of Minister of Transport, succeeding [[Blade Nzimande]].<ref>[https://www.wheels24.co.za/News/new-minister-of-transport-what-should-fikile-mbalula-focus-on-to-improve-road-safety-20190530 New Minister of Transport: What should Fikile Mbalula focus on to improve road safety?]. Retrieved on 11 June 2019.</ref>\n\n==Controversial statements==\nKnown for his disregard for speaking conventions,<ref name=\"n24_mockering\">{{cite web | url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Are-you-mockering-me-20071219 | title=Are you mockering me | publisher=News24 | accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> Mbalula has several times made headlines with controversial statements. In June 2007 he likened the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]] to [[Bombay]], saying black students were left on the periphery while those of [[India]]n descent swelled the ranks.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=vn20070618092501312C917924 Mbalula's comment angers UKZN staff] ''Independent Online''</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, amid rising tensions in the run-up to the ANC's Polokwane conference, Mbalula wrote a letter to finance minister [[Trevor Manuel]] calling him arrogant and an \"[[attention-seeking]] drama queen\". This followed Manuel dismissing Mbalula as a \"self-appointed spokesperson of the national democratic revolution\".<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=vn20071214045007928C216401 'Drama queen' Manuel slammed by Mbalula] ''IOL''</ref>\n\nIn April 2008 Mbalula said that [[Barney Pityana]], rector of the [[University of South Africa]], had \"made a clown of himself by his overzealous confusion and comical postulations\" after Pityana expressed criticism of Zuma.\n\nIn January 2014, after [[Bafana Bafana]] were eliminated in the first round from the CHAN competition, Mbalula said that the national team were \"a bunch of losers\".<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/bafana/mbalula-useless-bafana-are-bunch-of-losers-1.1633820#.Ut4vHdL8LbE Mbalula:Useless Bafana are bunch of losers] ''IOL''</ref><ref>[http://mg.co.za/article/2014-01-20-bafana-a-bunch-of-losers-says-mbalula Bafana 'a bunch of losers', says Mbalula] ''Mail & Guardian''</ref>\n\nHe also once at a public meeting (in the presence of the media) chanted the [[Springboks]] rugby team on, ahead of their overseas tour, with the words \"Donner hulle...bliksem hulle\", to which the audience of supporters erupted in cheers.\n\nOn 25 April 2016, he suspended the privileges of SA Rugby, Cricket South Africa and Athletics SA from bidding for international tournaments due to lack of transformation.<ref>[http://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/mbalula-bans-sa-from-bidding-for-major-rugby-cricket-events-20160425' Mbalula bans SA from bidding for major rugby, cricket events] ''Sport24''</ref>\n\n==Controversial decisions==\nMbalula announced a total lock down of all borders and the closing of airports during the Covid 19 crisis. By changing the laws from all citizens may return to no citizens or tourists my leave or enter South Africa with very little warning, this left over 6000 tourists stranded within South Africa and approximately 3000 South African citizens stranded all over the world. Repatriation missions from Brazil and Germany due to political ties have taken place. Lock down began 27 March at midnight. Plans are yet to made the rescue the thousands of South Africans stranded. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=nw20091023073500983C702121 Asmal must 'die': MK Vets] ''IOL''\n\n{{SASportsMinisters}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mbalula, Fikile}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Free State (province)]]\n[[Category:Xhosa people]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:South African Ministers for Sport and Recreation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n|name               = Fikile Mbalula\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|honorific-suffix   = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image              = CGF Durban2022Bid-7747 (Fikile Mbalula cropped).jpg\n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = \n|president          = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|office             = [[Minister of Transport (South Africa)|Minister of Transport]]\n|term_start         = 30 May 2019\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = [[Blade Nzimande]]\n|successor          = \n|office2            = [[Minister of Police (South Africa)|Minister of Police]]\n|president2         = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start2        = 31 March 2017\n|term_end2 = 26 February 2018\n|predecessor2       = [[Nkosinathi Nhleko]]\n|successor2         = [[Bheki Cele]]\n|office3            = [[Minister of Sport and Recreation (South Africa)|Minister of Sport and Recreation]]\n|president3         = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start3        = 1 November 2010\n|term_end3          = 31 March 2017\n|predecessor3       = [[Makhenkesi Stofile]]\n|successor3         = [[Thembelani Nxesi]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1971|04|08}}\n|birth_place        = [[Botshabelo, Free State]]\n|death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place        = \n|birthname          = \n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|party              = [[African National Congress]]\n|otherparty         = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = \n|partner            = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n}}\n'''Fikile April Mbalula''' (born 8 April 1971<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps.gcis.gov.za/gcis/gcis_profile.jsp?id=6397 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804235648/http://apps.gcis.gov.za/gcis/gcis_profile.jsp?id=6397 |archivedate=2012-08-04 }}</ref> in the [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]]) is a South African politician who is currently serving as Minister of Transport. He previously served as both [[Minister of Police (South Africa)|Minister and Deputy Minister of Police]] and Minister of Sports and Recreation. Mbalula is a member of the National Executive Committee of the [[African National Congress]] and former leader of the [[African National Congress Youth League]].\n\n==Career==\nMbalula was appointed Deputy Minister of Police in the cabinet of Jacob Zuma in May 2009 and later became the Minister of Sport and Recreation after President Jacob Zuma changed his cabinet. On 31 March 2017, following a controversial reshuffling in the cabinet, Mbalula was appointed as Minister of Police taking over from [[Nkosinathi Nhleko|Nathi Nhleko]] <ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/Elections/News/0,,2-2478-2479_2514142,00.html New Cabinet \u2013 full appointments] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512103024/http://www.news24.com/News24/Elections/News/0,,2-2478-2479_2514142,00.html |date=May 12, 2009 }} ''News24''</ref> after lobbying from the ANC Youth League<ref>[http://www.sowetan.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=995024 ANCYL wants its cadres in top posts]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Sowetan''</ref><ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2514063,00.html Speculation about Zuma's cabinet] ''News24''</ref> and possibly as a reward for loyalty towards Zuma,<ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/Elections/News/0,,2-2478-2479_2513057,00.html Zuma's Cabinet: Who's in?] ''News24''</ref> according to media speculation.\n\nIn the [[2009 South African general election|2009 general elections]] he was the manager of the ANC election campaign, which was considered highly successful.<ref>[http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/topstories.aspx?ID=BD4A987045 Slick party machinery wins the day] ''Business Day''</ref>\n\nMbalula was elected to the ANC NEC at the party's [[Polokwane]] conference in December 2007 in 15th place, measured in the number of votes.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=vn20071221112828576C498669 Meet Jacob Zuma's A-team] ''IOL''</ref> He subsequently retired as president of the ANC Youth League of which, at age 36, he was no longer eligible to be a member.<ref>[http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2180863,00.html ANCYL president to retire at 36] ''News24''</ref>\n\nMbalula was elected president of the ANC Youth League in August 2004, having previously held the post of secretary general.<ref>[http://www.sabcnews.com/politics/the_parties/0,2172,86282,00.html ANC Youth League calls on members to put country first] ''SABC''</ref>\n\nMbalula has been credited with installing South African President Thabo Mbeki in that position, and for later deposing him as head of the ANC.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=vn20080111073807686C336747 Zuma's NWC vs Mbeki's cabinet] ''Independent Online''</ref> His support has also been described as key in gaining Zuma the ANC presidency in a hard-fought race with Mbeki.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22952688-5003402,00.html Zuma backers urge new direction] ''News.com.au''</ref>\n\nHe also supported the candidacy of [[Julius Malema]] to succeed him as head of the Youth League in what was seen as a move to ensure continuing League support for Zuma.<ref>[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-04-07-malema-elected-as-new-ancyl-leader Malema elected as new ANCYL leader] ''Mail & Guardian''</ref>\n\nApart from politics, he is an ardent supporter of the [[Kaizer Chiefs Football Club]], and the \"Minister of Twitter\".\n\nIn May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] appointed Mbalula to the post of Minister of Transport, succeeding [[Blade Nzimande]].<ref>[https://www.wheels24.co.za/News/new-minister-of-transport-what-should-fikile-mbalula-focus-on-to-improve-road-safety-20190530 New Minister of Transport: What should Fikile Mbalula focus on to improve road safety?]. Retrieved on 11 June 2019.</ref>\n\n==Controversial statements==\nKnown for his disregard for speaking conventions,<ref name=\"n24_mockering\">{{cite web | url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Are-you-mockering-me-20071219 | title=Are you mockering me | publisher=News24 | accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> Mbalula has several times made headlines with controversial statements. In June 2007 he likened the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]] to [[Bombay]], saying black students were left on the periphery while those of [[India]]n descent swelled the ranks.<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=vn20070618092501312C917924 Mbalula's comment angers UKZN staff] ''Independent Online''</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, amid rising tensions in the run-up to the ANC's Polokwane conference, Mbalula wrote a letter to finance minister [[Trevor Manuel]] calling him arrogant and an \"[[attention-seeking]] drama queen\". This followed Manuel dismissing Mbalula as a \"self-appointed spokesperson of the national democratic revolution\".<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=vn20071214045007928C216401 'Drama queen' Manuel slammed by Mbalula] ''IOL''</ref>\n\nIn April 2008 Mbalula said that [[Barney Pityana]], rector of the [[University of South Africa]], had \"made a clown of himself by his overzealous confusion and comical postulations\" after Pityana expressed criticism of Zuma.\n\nIn January 2014, after [[Bafana Bafana]] were eliminated in the first round from the CHAN competition, Mbalula said that the national team were \"a bunch of losers\".<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/bafana/mbalula-useless-bafana-are-bunch-of-losers-1.1633820#.Ut4vHdL8LbE Mbalula:Useless Bafana are bunch of losers] ''IOL''</ref><ref>[http://mg.co.za/article/2014-01-20-bafana-a-bunch-of-losers-says-mbalula Bafana 'a bunch of losers', says Mbalula] ''Mail & Guardian''</ref>\n\nHe also once at a public meeting (in the presence of the media) chanted the [[Springboks]] rugby team on, ahead of their overseas tour, with the words \"Donner hulle...bliksem hulle\", to which the audience of supporters erupted in cheers.\n\nOn 25 April 2016, he suspended the privileges of SA Rugby, Cricket South Africa and Athletics SA from bidding for international tournaments due to lack of transformation.<ref>[http://www.sport24.co.za/OtherSport/South-Africa/mbalula-bans-sa-from-bidding-for-major-rugby-cricket-events-20160425' Mbalula bans SA from bidding for major rugby, cricket events] ''Sport24''</ref>\n\n==Controversial decisions==\nMbalula announced a total lock down of all borders and the closing of airports during the Covid 19 crisis. By changing the laws from all citizens may return to no citizens or tourists my leave or enter South Africa with very little warning, this left over 6000 tourists stranded within South Africa and approximately 3000 South African citizens stranded all over the world. Repatriation missions from Brazil and Germany due to political ties have taken place. Lock down began 27 March at midnight. Plans are yet to made the rescue the thousands of South Africans stranded. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=nw20091023073500983C702121 Asmal must 'die': MK Vets] ''IOL''\n\n{{SASportsMinisters}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mbalula, Fikile}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Free State (province)]]\n[[Category:Xhosa people]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:South African Ministers for Sport and Recreation]]\n", "name_user": "Srollie", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fikile_Mbalula"}
{"title_page": "Name change", "text_new": "{{Selfref|For information on altering your own Wikipedia username, see [[Wikipedia:Changing username]].}}\n{{for|name changes of places rather than persons|Geographical renaming}}\n[[File:Navneforandring.jpg|thumb|right|Name change certificate issued by [[Christian X of Denmark]] in 1917]]\n'''A\u0399\u03bf\u03b7\u03b5 \u03b2\u03bf\u03b3 A\u03ba\u0397\u03b1\u03b7\u03b4 Name change''' generally refers to the legal act by a person of adopting a new name different from their name at birth, marriage or adoption.\n\nThe procedures and ease of a name change vary between jurisdictions. In general, [[common law]] jurisdictions have loose procedures for a name change while [[civil law (legal system)|civil law]] jurisdictions are more restrictive.\n\nA [[pseudonym]] is a name used in addition to the original or true name.  This does not require legal sanction. Pseudonyms are generally adopted to conceal a person's identity, but may also be used for personal, social or ideological reasons.\n\n==Reasons for changing one's name==\n* Marriage or civil partnership. \n* [[Divorce]] or [[Family estrangement|estrangement]] of parents.\n* To avoid a [[stalker]] or [[harassment]]\n* To choose a surname associated with a hobby, interest, or accomplishment (e.g., old name Henry Schifberg, new name [[Henry Lizardlover]])\n* To receive an inheritance conditional on adopting the name of the deceased (this reason was once quite common in landowning families in the UK)\n* To replace a frivolous name given by their parents (e.g., old name Mikey Maus, new name Marcus Maus)\n* To replace a name which might be considered undesirable with a more desirable one (e.g., old surname Lipschitz, new surname London)\n* To dissociate oneself from a former religion (e.g., Ahmed Abdullah to Adel Karim) \n* To dissociate themselves from a famous or infamous person (e.g., old name [[Michael Jackson]] new name Martin Jackson)\n* To identify with a famous or infamous person (e.g., old name Simon Johnson, new name Simon [[King Arthur|Pendragon]])\n* To dissociate themselves from a family [[Black sheep (term)|black sheep]] (e.g., relatives of [[Adolf Hitler]]).\n* To dissociate themselves from an ethnic origin (e.g., changing [[Battenberg family|Battenberg]] to [[Mountbatten]] or Jan Ludvik Hoch to [[Robert Maxwell]]).\n* To revert to a former name (e.g., [[Cynthia Lennon]], first wife of [[John Lennon]], after her divorce from later husband John Twist).\n* Commercial sponsorship (e.g., [[Jimmy White]] temporarily became Jimmy Brown for [[HP Sauce|HP brown sauce]],<ref name=\"BBCBrown1\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/funny_old_game/4245973.stm \"Jimmy Gets Saucy with Name Change\"], no by-line, ''BBC News'' (online edition), \"Sport: Fun and Games\" section, 8 February 2005; accessed 14 March 2007</ref> and [[Ashley Revell]] became Ashley blue square Revell for [[The Rank Group]]'s Blue Square service)\n* Protest or activism (e.g., old name Jennifer Taylor, new name Jennifer [[Environmentalism|Save the Forests]])\n* To change to a fictional character's name, (e.g., old name Tracy Darling, new name [[Tracy Beaker]])\n* To make their name more attractive or \"catchy\" so as to increase their chance of success (see [[Stage name]])\n* To change legal name to one used in everyday life (e.g., where middle name has been used throughout life)\n* To [[anglicise]] a name or choose a different name if one's name is too difficult to pronounce or spell for most people\n* To better fit one's [[gender identity]] as a [[transgender]] person (e.g., old name Bruce Jenner, new name [[Caitlyn Jenner]])\n\n==United States==\nIn the United States, [[State law (United States)|state law]]s regulate name changes. Several federal court rulings have set precedents regarding both court decreed name changes and [[common law]] name changes (changing the name at will), including ''[[Lindon v. First National Bank]]''.\n\nUsually a person can adopt any name desired for any reason. As of 2009, 46 states allow a person legally to change names by usage alone, with no paperwork, but a court order may be required for many institutions (such as banks or government institutions) to officially accept the change.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Julia Shear|last=Kushner|url=https://uclalawreview.org/pdf/57-1-7.pdf|title=The Right to Control One's Name|work=[[UCLA Law Review]]|issue=313|year=2009|pages=324\u20139}} The states which require a statutory name-change procedure are Hawaii, Louisiana, Maine, and Oklahoma.</ref>  Although the states ([[Law of Louisiana|except Louisiana]]) follow common law, there are differences in acceptable requirements; usually a [[court order]] is the most efficient way to change names (which would be applied for in a [[State court (United States)|state court]]), except at marriage, which has become a universally accepted reason for a name change.\n\nWhere a court process is used, it is necessary to [[pleading|plead]] that the name change is not for a [[fraud]]ulent or other illegal purpose, such as evading a [[lien]] or [[debt]] or for [[defamation|defaming]] someone else.  Applicants may be required to give a reasonable explanation for wanting to change their names. A fee is generally payable, and the applicant may be required to post legal notices in newspapers to announce the name change. Generally the judge has limited [[judicial discretion]] to deny a change of name: usually only if the name change is for fraudulent, frivolous or [[Morality|immoral]] purposes.<ref>Edward J. Bander, ''Change of Name and Law of Names'' (Dobbs Ferry, New York: Oceana Publications, 1973) Ch. 2&ndash;3.</ref>  In 2004, a [[Missouri]] man succeeded in changing his name to They.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/offbeat/2004-09-23-name-change_x.htm|work=USA Today|title=Missouri man legally changes his name to 'They'}}</ref> The [[Minnesota Supreme Court]] ruled that a name change to 1069 could be denied, but that Ten Sixty-Nine was acceptable (''Application of Dengler'', 1979); the [[North Dakota Supreme Court]] had denied the same request several years before (''Petition of Dengler'', 1976).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.court.state.nd.us/court/opinions/9205.htm|title=Petition of Dengler, 246 N.W.2d 758 (N.D. 1976)|work=state.nd.us}}</ref>\n\nIn nearly all states, a person cannot choose a name that is intended to mislead (such as adopting a celebrity's name), that is intentionally confusing, or that incites violence; nor can one adopt, as a name, a [[racial slur]], a threat, or an [[obscene|obscenity]].\n\nSome examples of typically allowed reasons for name changes in the U.S. include:\n* Adopting a new surname upon marriage (typically the surname of the spouse, a [[hyphenated name|hyphenated surname]], or some combination of parts of both surnames).  This is usually done without court proceedings.\n* Returning to the use of a prior surname (e.g., a [[maiden name]]) upon divorce.\n* Simplification or improved familiarity of spelling or pronunciation.\n\nUnder the federal immigration-and-nationality law, when aliens apply for [[naturalization]], they have the option of asking for their names to be changed upon the grants of citizenship with no additional fees. This allows them the opportunity to adopt more [[Cultural assimilation#Immigrant name changing as a form of assimilation|Americanized]] names.<ref>\"[http://www.uscis.gov/files/form/n-400.pdf N-400 Application for Naturalization]\", (US Citizenship and Immigration Services, 2011).</ref> During the naturalization interview, a petition for a name change is prepared to be forwarded to a [[United States federal courts|federal court]]. Applicants certify that they are not seeking a change of name for any unlawful purpose such as the avoidance of debt or evasion of [[Police|law enforcement]]. Such a name change would become final if within their jurisdiction, once a [[United States federal courts|federal court]] naturalizes an applicant.\n\nTo maintain a person's [[identity (social science)|identity]], it is desirable to obtain a formal order so there is continuity of personal records.\n\n===Informal methods of legal name change===\n\n====Assumed name====\nThe \"open and notorious\" use of a name is often sufficient to allow one to use an [[assumed name]]. In some jurisdictions, a trade name distinct from one's legal name can be registered with a county clerk, [[Secretary of State (U.S. state government)|secretary of state]], or other similar government authority. Persons who wish to publish materials and not to be associated with them may publish under [[pseudonym]]s; such a right is protected under [[case law]] pursuant to [[United States Constitution]].\n\n====Usage method====\nA common law name (i.e. one assumed without formality and for a non-fraudulent purpose) is a legal name.<ref>See, ''e.g.'', ''State v. Ford'', 172 P. 802; ''Bonnie Lee Daniels'', 337 A.2d 49; ''Elizabeth Marie Hauptly'' 312 N.E.2d 857; ''Piotrowski v. Piotrowski'', 247 N.W.2d 354; ''Thomas v. Thomas'', 427 N.E.2d 1009; ''Klein v. Klein'', 373 A.2d 86; ''Stuart v. Board of Elections'', 295 A.2d 223.</ref> In most states a statutory method, while quick and definitive, only supplements the common law method,<ref>''In Matter of Linda A.'', 480 N.Y.S.2d 996.</ref> unless the statute makes itself exclusive. Although a person may sue under a common law name.<ref>''Hoffman v. Bank of America'', (M.D. Florida 2006).</ref>\n\nIn [[California]] the \"usage method\" (changing the name at will under common law) is sufficient to change the name.  Not all jurisdictions require that the new name be used exclusively.<ref>For example, ''Kreuter v US'', 201 F2d 33 (true name need not be abandoned), Florida Statute 322.22 (driver's licenses in two names), ''Loser v. Plainfield'', 128 N.W. 1101 (Iowa), ''Ludwinska v John Hancock'', 317 Pa 577 (may be used for just one nonfraudulent transaction).</ref> Any fraudulent use or intent, such as changing the name to the same name as another person's name, may invalidate this type of name change.\n\nSpecifically in California, Code of Civil Procedure \u00a7 1279.5 and Family Code \u00a7 2082 regulate common law and court decreed name changes. Code of Civil Procedure \u00a7 1279.5 (a) reads, \"Except as provided in subdivision (b), (c), (d), or (e), nothing in this title shall be construed to abrogate the common law right of any person to change his or her name.\" Subdivisions b through e preclude one from changing their name by common law if they are in state prison, on probation, on parole, or have been convicted of a serious sex offense. If a person is not in any of these categories, then a common law name change is allowed. (Family Code \u00a7 2082 also contains some of the same wording.)\n\n====Preferred name====\nMany universities, hospitals, and other institutions allow one to use a \"preferred name\" instead of one's legal name.  This name can show up on class rosters, online learning platforms, and [[student ID]] cards.  It provides a \"transitional\"\nname change for those who have yet to, or cannot, receive a court-ordered name change.<ref name=\"UC Davis\">{{cite web|title=Preferred Name {{!}} Office of the University Registrar|url=https://registrar.ucdavis.edu/records/preferred-name.cfm|website=registrar.ucdavis.edu|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Leicester\">{{cite web|title=What is a preferred first name or preferred last name? \u2014 University of Leicester|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/hr/policies/ess/Questions/what-is-a-preferred-first-name-or-preferred-last-name|website=www2.le.ac.uk|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Official registration===\nA legal name change is merely the first step in the name-change process. A person must officially register the new name with the appropriate authorities whether the change was made as a result of a court order, marriage, divorce, adoption, or any of the other methods described above. The process includes notifying various government agencies, each of which may require legal proof of the name change and that may or may not charge a fee. Important government agencies to be notified include the [[Social Security Administration]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://faq.ssa.gov/link/portal/34011/34019/Article/3749/|title=How do I change or correct my name on my Social Security number card?|work=ssa.gov|access-date=2015-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102072805/https://faq.ssa.gov/link/portal/34011/34019/Article/3749/|archive-date=2016-01-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Bureau of Consular Affairs]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/passport/npic/agencies/agencies_913.html|title=U.S. Passports & International Travel|work=state.gov}}</ref> (for [[United States passport|passports]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fam.state.gov/FAM/08FAM/08FAM040301.html |title=8 FAM 403.1-4 Material Discrepancies (Major name changes) |last= |first= |date=August 7, 2018 |website=Foreign Affairs Manual |publisher=United States Department of State |access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> the [[Federal Communications Commission]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transition.fcc.gov/Forms/Form605/605.html|title=FCC Form 605|author=FCC Internet Services Staff|work=fcc.gov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422032207/http://transition.fcc.gov/Forms/Form605/605.html|archivedate=2014-04-22}}</ref> the [[Selective Service System]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sss.gov/regisrantsbk.htm#RegistrantObligations|title=Selective Service System: Registrant Obligations|website=www.sss.gov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329020540/http://www.sss.gov/regisrantsbk.htm#RegistrantObligations|archivedate=2015-03-29}}</ref> and the Department of Motor Vehicles (for a new driver's license, learner permit, state identification card, or vehicular registration). Additionally the new name must be registered with other institutions such as employers, banks, doctors, mortgage, insurance and credit card companies. Online services are available to assist in this process either through direct legal assistance or automated form processing.\n\nMost states require name changes to be registered with their departments of motor vehicles (DMVs) within a certain amount of time, and some state motor vehicle departments require updated social security cards to make changes, by first registering a new name with the Social Security office:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Several United States !! Time limits in days !! Notes\n|-\n|[[Arizona]] || 10 || Must appear in person with updated social security cards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://azdot.gov/motor-vehicles/driver-services/driver-license-information/change-your-address-or-name|title=Motor Vehicle Services|work=azdot.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Connecticut]] || Undefined || Must appear in person with updated social security cards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portal.ct.gov/DMV/Easy-Answers/Easy-Answers-Webpages/Change-of-Name|title=DMV Easy Answers for Change of Name|work=Department of Motor Vehicles}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Delaware]] || 30 || Must appear in person with updated social security cards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmv.de.gov/VehicleServices/titles/index.shtml?dc=ve_title_name|title=Requirements for Change of Name and Address|work=Division of Motor Vehicles|accessdate=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Illinois]] || 30 || <ref>[http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/rules_of_the_road/rr_chap01.html#changing_name_address] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070427004533/http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/rules_of_the_road/rr_chap01.html#changing_name_address|date=April 27, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Maryland]] || Undefined || Must appear in person<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mva.maryland.gov/drivers/apply/md-drivers-license.htm#mddlcorrecting|title=Maryland Driver's License: Correcting/Changing Your Maryland License or Permit|work=Motor Vehicle Administration}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[New Jersey]] || Undefined || Must appear in person<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.nj.us/mvc/drivertopics/namechange.htm|title=Name Change|work=New Jersey Motor Vehicle Commission}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[New York (state)|New York]] || Undefined || Must appear in person<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmv.ny.gov/dmvfaqs.htm#name|title=New York State DMV|work=New York State DMV|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626065446/http://www.dmv.ny.gov/dmvfaqs.htm#name|archivedate=2012-06-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[North Carolina]] || 60 || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdot.org/dmv/driver_services/drivershandbook/chapter1/renewalLicense.html#RDNameChanges|title=NCDOT: License and ID|work=[[North Carolina Department of Transportation]]|access-date=2007-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212202302/http://www.ncdot.org/dmv/driver_services/drivershandbook/chapter1/renewalLicense.html#RDNameChanges|archive-date=2007-12-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Pennsylvania]] || Undefined || Must appear in person for a driver's license or photo ID<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmv.pa.gov/Driver-Services/Driver-Licensing/Pages/Change-Your-Name-or-Address.aspx|title=Change Your Name or Address|work=DMV}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[South Carolina]] || 10 || <ref>http://www.scdmvonline.com/DMVNew/default.aspx?n=general_driver_license_information#NameorAddressChanges {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228092155/http://www.scdmvonline.com/DMVNew/default.aspx?n=general_driver_license_information |date=2012-12-28 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Texas]] || 30 || <ref>[http://www.txdps.state.tx.us/administration/driver_licensing_control/faq/answers_dl_id.htm#q18] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012023946/http://www.txdps.state.tx.us/administration/driver_licensing_control/faq/answers_dl_id.htm#q18|date=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Vermont]] || 30 || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmv.vermont.gov/licenses/change-name-address|title=Change Address or Name on Your License \u2013 Department of Motor Vehicles|website=dmv.vermont.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wyoming]] || 10 || <ref>[http://dot.state.wy.us/Default.jsp?sCode=drvna] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070919202553/http://dot.state.wy.us/Default.jsp?sCode=drvna|date=September 19, 2007}}</ref>\n|}\nThe fees for registering a new name vary from state to state. The forms, along with the state-specific requirements, can generally be obtained for free.\n\nMany states will require reasons for wanting a name change. For example, in Florida, a court will not grant a petition for a change of name if it finds that (i) the petitioner has ulterior or illegal motives in seeking the name change, (ii) the petitioner's civil rights are suspended, or (iii) granting the name change will invade the property rights (''e.g.'', intellectual property rights) of others.<ref>see, e.g., [http://abcfamilylaw.com/practice-areas/change-of-name www.abcfamilylaw.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128015829/http://www.abcfamilylaw.com/practice-areas/change-of-name |date=2010-11-28 }}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\nIn the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]], citizens and residents have the freedom to change their names with relative ease.\n\nIn theory, anyone who is at least 16 and resident in the United Kingdom can call themselves whatever they wish. However, over the past hundred years or so, formal procedures that are recognized by record holders such as government departments, companies and organizations have evolved, which enable a citizen legally to change the name recorded on their [[passport]], [[driving licence]], tax and [[National Insurance]] records, bank and credit cards, etc., provided that \"documentary evidence\" of a change of name is provided. Documents such as [[birth certificate|birth]], [[marriage certificate|marriage]] and educational certificates cannot be changed because these documents are \"matters of fact\", which means that they were correct at the time they were issued.\n\nDocumentary evidence of a change of name can be in a number of forms, such as a marriage certificate, [[decree absolute]], civil partnership certificate, [[statutory declaration]] or [[deed of change of name]]. Such documents are mere evidence that a change of name has occurred, however, and they do not themselves operate to change a person's name. Deeds of change of name are by far the most commonly used method of providing evidence of a change of name other than changing a woman's surname after marriage. A deed poll is a legal document that binds a single person to a particular course of action (in this case, changing one's name for all purposes). The term 'deed' is common to signed, written agreements that have been shown to all concerned parties. Strictly speaking, it is not a contract because it binds only one party and expresses an intention instead of a promise. 'Poll' is an old legal term referring to official documents that had cut edges (were polled) so that they were straight.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/files/deedpolls_notes_0308.doc ''Enrolling a Name Change in the Royal Courts of Justice''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002143613/http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/files/deedpolls_notes_0308.doc |date=2008-10-02 }} (March 2008). Her Majesty's Courts Service. Retrieved September 12, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/9805.htm#deed_polls ''Judgement and Orders Section''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606115033/http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/9805.htm |date=2011-06-06 }}(March 26, 2008). Her Majesty's Courts Service. \u00a7 Deed Polls. Retrieved September 12, 2008.</ref>\n\n===England and Wales===\nPeople whose births are registered in England and Wales may have their [[deed poll]] enrolled at the [[Royal Courts of Justice]] in [[London]].<ref>[https://deedpolloffice.com/pdf/phillimore_and_fry_index.pdf www.deedpolloffice.com]</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> See also [[College of Arms#Change of names]].\n\n====Historical usage====\n{{See also|Double-barrelled name#British tradition}}\nFrom the medi\u00e6val age to the 19th century, the era of family dynasties, name changes were frequently demanded of heirs in the last wills and testaments, legacies and bequests, of members of the gentry and nobility who were the last males of their bloodline. Such persons frequently selected a younger nephew or cousin as the heir to their estates on condition that he should adopt the surname and armorials of the legator in lieu of his patronymic. Thus the ancient family otherwise destined to extinction would appear to continue as a great dynasty in the making. Such changes were also more rarely demanded by [[marriage settlement]]s, for example where the father of a sole daughter and heiress demanded that as a condition of his daughter's [[dowry]] her husband should adopt his father-in-law's surname and arms. Thus the progeny of the marriage would continue the otherwise extinct family's name. Such name changes were generally only demanded of younger sons, where an elder brother was available to inherit the paternal estates under primogeniture and carry on the name and arms abandoned by the younger brother. Such name changes were effected by obtaining a private [[Act of Parliament]] or by obtaining a [[College of Arms|Royal Licence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deedpolloffice.com/research#royal-licences|title=Researching a past change of name \u2013 D\u2022P\u2022O|work=Deed Poll Office}}</ref> A less radical procedure adopted from the 18th century onwards was for the legator or settlor to demand only that the legatee or beneficiary should adopt his surname ''in addition to'' his patronymic, not in place of it, which gave rise to the \"[[Double-barrelled name|double-barrelled]]\", even the \"triple-barrelled\" name, frequently parodied in literature as epitomising the wealthy \"[[squirearchy]]\" with an embarrassment of inherited estates.\n\nWell known examples are:\n*Russell to Gorges (14th century). Ralph IV Gorges, 2nd Baron Gorges, died without issue in 1331. In an effort to preserve his family name and arms he made one of his younger nephews his heir, on condition that he should adopt the name and arms of Gorges. This nephew was William Russell, the second son of his second sister Eleanor de Gorges who had married Sir Theobald Russell (d.1341) of [[Kingston Russell]], Dorset. The event is referred to in one of the earliest heraldic law cases brought concerning English armory, [[Warbelton v. Gorges]] in 1347.\n*Smithson to Percy (18th century). [[Hugh Percy, 1st Duke of Northumberland|Sir Hugh Smithson, 4th Baronet]] (1715\u20131786) (c.1714\u20131786) in 1740 married [[Elizabeth Percy, Duchess of Northumberland|Lady Elizabeth Seymour]], daughter and sole heiress of [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset]], and granddaughter of Lady Elizabeth Percy (d.1722), daughter and sole heiress of [[Josceline Percy, 11th Earl of Northumberland]] (1644\u20131670). In 1740, by a private Act of Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deedpolloffice.com/research/private-acts-parliament/1749-23-Geo-2-14|title=Hugh Earl of Northumberland's name and arms. \u2013 D\u2022P\u2022O|work=Deed Poll Office}}</ref> Smithson changed his surname to Percy and inherited the title [[Earl of Northumberland]] and was later created [[Duke of Northumberland]].\n\n===Scotland===\nPeople whose births are [[civil registration|registered]] in Scotland (or who were adopted in Scotland) can change their name in the same way as people from the rest of the United Kingdom.  However they can optionally apply to the [[Registrar General for Scotland]] to have their birth certificate amended to show the new name and have the respective register updated.\n\n==Other common law countries==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIndividuals may legally change their name through the [[States and territories of Australia|state and territory]] governments of Australia according to state or territory laws and regulations via agencies generally titled \"Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australia.gov.au/information-and-services/family-and-community/births-deaths-and-marriages-registries|title=Births, deaths and marriages registries \u2013 australia.gov.au|first=Digital Transformation|last=Agency|website=www.australia.gov.au}}</ref>  Exceptions exist for some states such as restricted persons (e.g. jail inmate)<ref>http://www.bdm.nsw.gov.au/Pages/change-of-name/change-of-name.aspx</ref> and in some states, changes may only be made once a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qld.gov.au/law/births-deaths-marriages-and-divorces/changing-your-name/changing-your-name/|title=Changing your name \u2013 Your rights, crime and the law|first=; c=AU; o=The State of Queensland; ou=Communication Services|last=Branch|website=www.qld.gov.au}}</ref>\n\nInstitutions such as banks,<ref>http://www.austrac.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/cip_form_ind_mar08.pdf</ref> the Passports Office<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.passports.gov.au/passportsexplained/theapplicationprocess/eligibilityoverview/Pages/confirmingidentity.aspx|title=Documents that confirm your Australian citizenship and identity|first=Australian Passports|last=Office|website=www.passports.gov.au}}</ref> and transport authorities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transport.wa.gov.au/licensing/change-my-name.asp|title=Change my name|first=|last=nw|website=www.transport.wa.gov.au}}</ref> require proof of identity, so people who change their names need to have proof of the change.\n\nIf a person's birth or adoption was registered in Australia, the change will also be noted (in most cases) on the person's birth or adoption registration, and in some states or territories, the name change can be evidenced either through a re-issued [[Birth certificate#Australia|birth certificate]] if born in Australia and/or \"Change of Name Certificate\".  These certificates are recognised secure [[Identity documents of Australia|identity documents]] and can be verified electronically through the [[Attorney-general of Australia]]'s Document Verification Service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx|title=Document Verification Service|first=Attorney-General's|last=Department|website=www.ag.gov.au|access-date=2017-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321081501/https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx|archive-date=2017-03-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{Australian Identity Documents}}\n\n===Canada===\nAll Canadian provinces and territories except Quebec allow their residents, whether Citizens, Permanent Residents or Temporary Residents, to obtain a name change, provided they fulfil the pertinent regulations (e.g. time lived in province) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ccla.org/frequently-asked-questions-regarding-change-of-name-for-trans-persons/|title=Frequently Asked Questions Regarding Change of Name for Trans Persons|date=2015-05-19|website=Canadian Civil Liberties Association|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>. Quebec, being a civil law jurisdiction, has substantial differences from the rest of Canada in how it permits its residents to obtain a change of name; further information is available in the Quebec section of the article.\n\n===Hong Kong===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2010}}\nIt is a common practice for ethnic Chinese residents of Hong Kong to adopt a western-style English name in addition to their transliterated Chinese name. As they often adopt western-style English names after being registered on the birth register, the fact that they want to include a western-style English name as part of their [[Legal name|legal English name]] is regarded as a name change which usually requires a deed poll.\n\nHowever, the [[Immigration Department (Hong Kong)|Immigration Department]] which is responsible for processing applications for name change allows applicants to submit such applications without deeds poll; anyone who has a phonetic English name only and wishes to include a western-style English name as part of his or her legal English name can apply to the Immigration Department without a deed poll. Only one application of this kind is allowed for each applicant; any application for subsequent change(s) must be made with a deed poll.\n\n===Ireland===\nIn the [[Republic of Ireland]], a person earns their name by \"use and repute\".<ref name=\"citizensinformation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensinformation.ie/en/birth_family_relationships/problems_in_marriages_and_other_relationships/changing_your_name_by_deed_poll.html|title=Changing your name by deed poll|website=www.citizensinformation.ie}}</ref> For most purposes it is enough to simply use the desired name and ask others to call you by that name.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> This was the traditional practice for a bride adopting her husband's surname.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> A [[deed of change of name|change of name deed poll]] is not required, but provides documentary evidence of a name change.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> Resident non-[[Citizenship of the European Union|EU nationals]] must apply to the [[Irish Naturalisation and Immigration Service]] for a deed poll.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> The deed poll requires a witness [[affidavit]], and may optionally be enrolled in the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] upon payment of [[stamp duty]].<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> An enrolled deed poll is required for some administrative name changes, such as on a [[Driving licence in the Republic of Ireland|driving licence]]<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> or when [[Transgender rights in Ireland|changing legal gender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensinformation.ie/en/birth_family_relationships/changing_to_your_preferred_gender.html|title=Changing to your preferred gender|website=www.citizensinformation.ie}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nFrom September 1995, [[New Zealanders]] can change their name by making a [[statutory declaration]] and, if approved, the new name is registered with the Births, Deaths and Marriages section of the Department of Internal Affairs (Identity Services). Prior to September 1995, they changed their name by [[deed poll]].<ref>[http://www.dia.govt.nz/diawebsite.nsf/Files/EOIStandard/$file/EOIStandard.pdf Evidence of Identity Standard] NZ Department of Internal Affairs, June 2006, Version 1.0, {{ISBN|0-478-24462-2}}, page 123</ref>\n\n==Civil law==\nIn general, unlike in [[common law]] countries, names cannot be changed at will in [[civil law (legal system)|civil law]] jurisdictions. Usually, a name change requires government approval and is only rarely granted, though legal name changes have become more common in some jurisdictions over the last years. The reason given for this system is usually the public interest in the unique identifiability of a person, e.g., in governmental registers, although with the advent of [[personal identification numbers]], that rationale may be in need of reconsideration.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n\n===Belgium===\nChanges in law Aug 2018 changes first name and fee will fall under the authority of local town hall <ref>https://justitie.belgium.be/nl/nieuws/persberichten_70</ref> In Belgian law, a name is in principle considered fixed for life, but under exceptional circumstances, a person may apply to the Ministry of Justice for a name change. This requires a Royal Decree (French: ''Arr\u00eat\u00e9 royal'', Dutch: ''Koninklijk besluit'') for last names, but only a Ministerial Decree for first names. The new name must not cause confusion or cause damage to the bearer or others. Examples of requests that are usually considered favorably:\n* A person of non-European origin who wants to adopt a less exotic name to further his/her integration in Belgian society\n* A person stuck with a ridiculous last name that is causing him/her great embarrassment or emotional distress. Actual examples: Salami, Naaktgeboren (\"born naked\"), and Clooten (\"sods of earth\" in Middle Dutch, but \"testicles\" in modern Dutch)\n* (for minor children) following legal adoption or recognition of paternity<ref>[http://www.just.fgov.be/nl_htm/informatie/htm_justitie_atotz/naamveranderen.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514153237/http://www.just.fgov.be/nl_htm/informatie/htm_justitie_atotz/naamveranderen.html|date=May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\nAccording to the Brazilian Civil Code and the Public Registries Act, the name registered after birth is definitive and immutable. However, there are some circumstances under which a name change is allowed: \n* If an obvious writing error is made while registering the name of the child.  \n* In the first year after a person reaches the [[age of majority]] (18&nbsp;years), they can request a change in their first names, but modification of surnames is not allowed.  \n* If a person's name exposes them to ridicule and harms their everyday well-being.  \n* If a person is recognized publicly by another name, they can request a name change or addition, by providing as support three testimonials of the change in name.  \n* If a person has undergone a sex change, recent jurisprudence has allowed name modifications in most such cases.\n\n===India===\nIn India, the person concerned submits a name change request to an appropriate authority, with supporting documents. Subsequently, an application must be made to the Government Printing Press, which issues an Official Gazette Notification certifying the change of name.<ref>http://goaprintingpress.gov.in/uploads/Change%20of%20Name%20and%20Surname%20Act.pdf</ref>\n\n===Norway===\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2012}}\nAlthough it has always been relatively easy to change one's legal names in Norway, it used to require some kind of government approval. As late as 1830, local vicars were instructed to write both given (Christian) names, as well as last names, in the baptismal record. Earlier, only the given name of the child, birth date, baptismal date, and sex were written down, alongside the parents' names. It was not until the beginning of the 20th century, however, that the authorities required everyone to adopt a family surname. Until about 1980, the government still required that a name change applicant apply to the government regional representative (fylkesmann). The law has been replaced twice since then. Nowadays, the process is as easy as in common-law countries; the subject merely submits the names wanted (providing that the surname chosen is not in use or is not used by fewer than 200 persons) to the local authorities for the purposes of election rosters and census counts; there is no longer an application process.\n\n===Philippines===\n2001 RA 9048 amends Articles 376 and 412 of the [[Civil Code of the Philippines]], which prohibit the change of name or surname of a person, or any correction or change of entry in a civil register without a judicial order. Administrative Order No. 1 Series of 2001, implemented the law.<ref>[https://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/irr_ra9048.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621060551/http://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/irr_ra9048.html|date=June 21, 2008}}</ref> It authorizes the city or municipal civil registrar or the consul general to correct a clerical or typographical error in an entry or change the first name or nickname in the civil register without need of a judicial order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/primerra9048.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212183553/http://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/primerra9048.html|archivedate=February 12, 2012|website=census.gov.ph|title= Civil Registration \u2013 Primer for RA 9048}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicactno9048.htm|title=PHILIPPINE LAWS, STATUTES AND CODES \u2013 CHAN ROBLES VIRTUAL LAW LIBRARY|work=chanrobles.com}}</ref>\n\n====Name and gender change====\nIn case of controversial and substantial changes, [[Philippines]] [[jurisprudence]] requires full-blown court [[lawsuit]], that must include the local civil registrar in the petition, since RA 9048 and Rule 108 (Cancellation or correction of entries in the Civil Registry) of the Rules of Court do not allow the change of sex in a birth certificate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/rulesofcourtspecialproceedings.htm#RULE%20108|title=SPECIAL PROCEEDINGS|work=chanrobles.com}}</ref>\n\nThe only landmark case in the Philippines on name and legal sex change is the Jeff Cagandahan case. The [[Supreme Court of the Philippines]] Justice [[Leonardo Quisumbing]] on September 12, 2008, allowed Cagandahan, 27, who has [[congenital adrenal hyperplasia]], to change his [[birth certificate]] name from Jennifer to Jeff, and his legal gender from female to male.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080917-161148/Call-him-Jeff-says-SC-he-used-to-be-called-Jennifer|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808193038/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080917-161148/Call-him-Jeff-says-SC-he-used-to-be-called-Jennifer|archivedate=August 8, 2014|title=Call him Jeff, says SC; he used to be called Jennifer|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,24359150-401,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216041937/http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,24359150-401,00.html|archivedate=February 16, 2009|title=Woman's body 'naturally' became male|work=[[News.com.au]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,423242,00.html|title=Rare Condition Turns Woman Into Man|work=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n===Quebec===\nIn Quebec, only Citizens may obtain a change of name from the Directeur de l'Etat Civil. Permanent Residents residing in Quebec, if falling under an [[Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada]] exception, may make a statutory declaration to IRCC and obtain a change of name through them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/corporate/publications-manuals/operational-bulletins-manuals/identity-management/exceptions.html|title=Exceptions to change of name requirements|last=Immigration|first=Refugees and Citizenship Canada|date=2017-11-16|website=aem|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> Otherwise, as with all Temporary Residents residing in Quebec, they must obtain a change of name from the country that issued their passport/travel document.\n\nQuebec also has other strict regulations regarding name changes. For example, Micheline Montreuil, a trans woman who is non-operative, had to undergo a lengthy process to have her name legally changed. Initially, the Directeur de l'Etat Civil refused to permit the change on the grounds that someone legally assigned male at birth could not bear a female name. According to Quebec law, Montreuil could not change her record of sex because this requires proof of a completed [[sex reassignment surgery]], which she has not had. On November 1, 1999, the provincial court of appeals ruled that nothing in the law prevented a person who was legally male from legally adopting a woman's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.micheline.ca/page034-batailles-e.htm#dictateur|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212004926/http://www.micheline.ca/page034-batailles-e.htm|archivedate=February 12, 2012|title=Micheline Anne H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Montreuil and his fights|website=micheline.ca}}</ref> Another issue specific to Quebec is married names. Because of the [[Quebec Charter of Rights]], married women in Quebec have been unable to adopt their spouse's surname since 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3940094/maiden-married-names-countries/|title=Here Are Places Women Can't Take Their Husband's Name When They Get Married|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> Other provinces allow their residents to change their last name on the strength of their [[Marriage certificate|marriage certificate.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.programs.alberta.ca/Living/5962.aspx?Ns=364+6228&N=770|title=Government of Alberta \u2013 Programs and Services \u2013 Getting Married|author=Government of Alberta|work=alberta.ca}}</ref>\n\nThe Directeur de l'Etat Civil will amend a Quebec birth certificate if a name change certificate is issued by another province. Some have used that loophole to legally change their names by temporarily moving another Canadian province or territory, which follow more permissive common-law rules.\n\n===South Africa===\nSouth Africa, which uses a mixture of common law and civil [[Roman Dutch law]], mostly uses common-law procedures with regard to name change. Name changes in [[South Africa]] are regulated by the Births and Deaths Registration Act (Act 51 of 1992, as amended). The personal information of all citizens and permanent residents is recorded on the Population Register, so any name changes must be registered.\n\nA person can change their forenames by submitting a form to the [[South African Department of Home Affairs|Department of Home Affairs]]. An individual's surname, or that of a family, may be changed by applying to the Department and providing a \"good and sufficient reason\" for the change.\n\nA married woman can change her surname to that of her husband or join her maiden name with her husband's surname, and a divorced woman may return to her previous surname, without applying or paying a fee; but she must notify the department so that the details in the Population Register can be changed. (It is possible that, if challenged, these provisions might be held to be unconstitutional because they apply only to women.)\n\nSouth Africa has officially recognized same sex marriages since 2006 and in doing so now allows one or both partners to change their surnames in the marriage register on the day of the marriage. A new passport and ID book can then be applied for with the new married surname as well.\n\nThe surnames of minor children can also be changed under various circumstances involving the marriage, divorce or death of a parent, children born out of wedlock, and guardianship.<ref>[http://www.home-affairs.gov.za/personal_amendments.asp ''Personal Amendments.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911222143/http://www.home-affairs.gov.za/personal_amendments.asp |date=2008-09-11 }} (c. 1997). South African Department of Home Affairs. Retrieved May 19, 2010</ref>\n\n===Switzerland===\nIn Switzerland, a name change requires the approval of the respective [[Cantons of Switzerland|Cantonal]] government, if there are important reasons (''wichtige Gr\u00fcnde'' / ''justes motifs'') for the change, according to article 30 of the [[Swiss Civil Code]]. When aliens apply for naturalization, they have the option of asking for their names to be changed upon the grants of citizenship with no additional fees.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} According to the case law of the [[Swiss Federal Supreme Court]], such requests must be granted only if the petitioner shows that they suffer substantially from their present name, e.g., if it is the same as that of a notorious criminal.\n\n===Taiwan===\n{{Wikibooks|Annotated Republic of China Laws/Name Act}}\nIn [[Taiwan]], the ''Name Act'' bans changing one's legal name for some criminal reasons per [https://law.moj.gov.tw/ENG/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=D0030011&norge=6 Article 15] since 2015 (Article 12 since 2001). Otherwise, one may change the surname, given name, or both per Article 8, 9, or 10 since 2015 (Article 5, 6, or 7 since 1953, or Article 6, 7, or 8 since 2001).\n\nChanging the given name is allowed if:<ref>Article 6 of the ''Name Act'' (1953) ([[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b42\u5e74)]]), amended into Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001) ([[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b90\u5e74)]]), then amended into Article 9 of the ''Name Act'' (2015) [[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b104\u5e74)]].</ref>\n#Having the same name when serving or studying in the same institution or school.\n#Since 1983, having the same given name as one's parent, grandparent, or great-grandparent.<ref>Clause 2 of Article 6 of the ''Name Act'' (1983) ([[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b72\u5e74)|\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b72\u5e74)]]), amended into Clause 2 of Section 1 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), then amended into Clause 2 of Section 1 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref>\n#Having the same name as someone else who lives in the same county or city and having lived there for at least 6 months.\n#Having the same name as a wanted criminal, for example [[:zh:\u9673\u9032\u8208|\u9673\u9032\u8208 (Ch\u00e9n J\u00ecnx\u012bng)]], a common name used by not only a convicted kidnapper and murderer who was executed in Taiwan for major crimes in 1997 ([[:zh:\u9673\u9032\u8208 (\u53f0\u7063\u7f6a\u72af)]]) but also a Taiwanese statesman ([[:zh:\u9673\u9032\u8208 (\u53f0\u7063\u653f\u6cbb\u4eba\u7269)]]).\n#Since 2015, acknowledgement by father or adoption starts or ends.\n#Having special reasons,<ref>Clause 6 of Section 1 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), amended into Clause 6 of Section 1 of Article 9 of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref> which is limited to thrice since 2015 (twice since 2001) in one's lifetime, while the second given name change of this type requires the age of majority.<ref>Section 2 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), amended into Section 2 of Article 9 of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref>\n\n====Replacing documents====\nDiplomas, work experience documents, licenses, permits, and other such documents shall use a person\u2019s legal name to avoid being deemed invalid<ref>Article 3 of the ''Name Act'' (1953), amended into Article 4 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), then amended into [https://law.moj.gov.tw/ENG/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=D0030011&norge=6 Article 6] of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref>, so those intending to change names have to note that:\n\nLicensed Taiwanese driver who legally changes the name without reporting to the competent traffic authority is fined 300 to 600 [[new Taiwan dollar]]s and asked to re-register the legal name.<ref>[https://law.moj.gov.tw/ENG/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=K0040012&norge=25 Article 25] of the ''Road Traffic Management and Penalty Act'' amended in 1986 and effective on 1 January 1987, having increased the administrative fine from 30 to 150 new Taiwan dollars effective on 1 May 1968 per \nClause 1 of Article 31 of the same ''Act'', and 150 to 300 new Taiwan dollars per Article 25 of the amendment in 1975 effective on 1 January 1976.</ref>\n{{Wikibooks|Annotated Republic of China Laws/Passport Act/2015}}\n[[Taiwan passport#Data page|Taiwan passports]] are to be replaced after having changed the names.<ref>Clause 3 of Section 1 of Article 19 of the ''Passport Act'' fully amended in 2015 effective on 1 January 2016, from Clause 3 of Section 1 of Article 15 of the ''Passport Act'' effective on 21 May 2000.</ref>\n\nRegistration of change in name of the right holder having been changed after a land right has been registered, shall be applied; the same shall apply to the change of the name of administrator.<ref>Section 1 of [https://law.moj.gov.tw/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=D0060003&norge=149 Article 149] of the ''Regulations of The Land Registration''</ref>\n\n====Overseas application====\n{{Wikibooks|Annotated Republic of China Regulations/Enforcement Rules of the Name Act}}\nA [[national without household registration]] may apply for name change outside Taiwan at a [[List of diplomatic missions of Taiwan|Taiwanese diplomatic mission]], but having had [[household registration in Taiwan]] may apply there only to forward a name change application to the Household Registration Office covering the last Taiwanese address of residency<ref>The last Section of Article 4 of the ''Enforcement Rules of the Name Act'' since 2001.</ref>, which is a better method only if no risk of discrepancies among Taiwanese documents, so anyone having considerable Taiwanese documents should still change the name in person at Taiwanese Household Registration Office, to also replace the [[National Identification Card (Republic of China)|National Identification Card]], [[Healthcare in Taiwan|healthcard card]], driver license, etc.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boca.gov.tw/cp-24-145-2695c-1.html |title=\u570b\u5916\u7533\u8acb\u8b77\u7167\u76f8\u95dc\u8cc7\u8a0a\uff1a\u4e00\u822c\u4eba\u6c11\u63db\u767c |last= |first= |date=2019-10-28 |website= |publisher=[[Bureau of Consular Affairs (Republic of China)]] |access-date=2019-11-22 |language=zh-hant|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Name change on religious conversion==\n{{further|Religious name}}\nAdherents of various religions change their name upon [[Religious conversion|conversion]] or confirmation. The name adopted may not have any legal status but will represent their adopted religious beliefs.<ref>Celia Emmelhainz, [http://works.bepress.com/emmelhainz/4/ ''Naming a New Self: Identity Elasticity and Self-Definition in Voluntary Name Changes.''] (c. 2012). Names, Vol. 60, Iss. 3. Retrieved April 4, 2016</ref>\n\n===Buddhism===\n* Individuals who attend a ceremony to officially become Buddhists are usually given a new \"[[Dharma name]]\", which marks their \"[[Refuge (Buddhism)|taking refuge]]\".\n\n===Christianity===\n* It has been historical Christian practice to adopt a name on [[baptism]] or (in some countries) [[confirmation (sacrament)|confirmation]].<ref>[http://www.catholic-forum.com/saints/ce001006.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050428082432/http://www.catholic-forum.com/saints/ce001006.htm|date=April 28, 2005}}</ref>\n* The customary practice whereby persons entering a [[religious institute]] take on a [[name in religion]] is still observed by [[Eastern Orthodox]] and some traditional [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]]. Eastern Orthodox monastics are usually given the name of a prophet or a monastic saint.\n* [[Pope]]s take a [[papal name]] upon their accession to office; for example, [[Jorge M. Bergoglio]] adopted the name [[Francis (given name)|Francis]].\n\n===Hinduism===\nThere is no formal concept of conversion in Hinduism but converts to Hinduism are accepted, usually after a small ceremony called [[Shuddhi|Shudhikaran]] (purification). Individuals who attend a Shudhikaran ceremony to officially become [[Hindu]] may be optionally given a new [[Dharma]] (religious) name, which is usually based on [[Sanskrit]] or [[Indian name]] such as names based on [[Hindu deities]].\n\n===Islam===\n* Converts to Islamic faith may choose a new name; although it is not required, it may in some cases be preferable for personal reasons or because the name is of uncertain Islamicity (e.g. the person converting has a [[theophoric name]] in another religion, such as Christopher or Ganesh). Boxer Cassius Clay's adoption of the name [[Muhammad Ali]] is a well-known example, as is Cat Stevens' change to [[Yusuf Islam]] and Malcolm Little's adoption of the name [[Malcolm X]] and later ''El-Hajj Malik El-Shabazz''.  On the other hand, converts may choose to keep their names, as did [[Dave Chappelle]].\n*Women do not normally take their husbands' surnames as their own. Their maiden name continues to be their surname even after marriage. Sometimes their husbands first name becomes their surname, similar to the case of surname chains indicating someone's chain of fathers. \n* In Islamic tradition, there are two kinds of [[surname]].\n:# The first kind comes from the father's first name, which means that the particular person is the child of. For example, a name such as ''ibn Abdullah'' means \"son of Abdullah\", or ''bint Abdullah'' means \"daughter of Abdullah\". Father descendant names can be chained, meaning that an individual can have the name of their father, followed by their paternal grandfather, followed by the father of that grandfather, to indicate a patrilineal lineage.\n:# The second kind is associated with [[clan]], [[tribal]] or [[ethnic]] affiliation and is also solely dependant on the person's patrilineal line. In Islamic family law, the individual is required to keep the clan, tribal or ethnic affiliation of their father where it is known, whether the child be illegitimate, staying with their mother after divorce or adopted.\nThe last name cannot be changed in such a way as to reflect a heritage that is not that of one's biological father.\n\n===Judaism===\n* Jewish people in the Diaspora sometimes give their children two names: a secular name for everyday use and a Hebrew name for religious purposes.  [[Conversion to Judaism|Converts to Judaism]] choose a Hebrew name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://judaism.about.com/library/3_lifecycles/names/bl_names.htm|title=Choosing a Hebrew Name \u2013 Naming a Jewish Baby|author=Ariela Pelaia|work=About.com Religion & Spirituality}}</ref> Full Jewish names include a [[patronym]]: converts take the patronym \"ben/bat Avraham Avinu\" (son/daughter of Our Father Abraham) as converts are held to be spiritual descendants of [[Abraham]], the forebear of Jews.\n\n===Sikhism===\n* Those in the [[Sikh]] faith adopt a new last name upon baptism into the [[Khalsa]]. Men adopt the last name [[Singh]], while women adopt the last name [[Kaur]].\n* The Sikhs adopted the name Singh in 1699 during the Birth of the Khalsa.\n\n===Wicca===\n* Some [[Wiccans]] have a [[craft name]] that is used during coven gatherings and rituals.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Family name]], including patrilineal surnames\n*[[Given name]]\n*[[Hornsleth Village Project]]\n*[[In re McUlta]]\n*[[Legal aspects of transsexualism]] for information about name change for transgender and transsexual people\n**[[Diane Marie Rodriguez Zambrano]], an activist who sued to enable legal name change in Ecuador for purposes of [[gender identity]]\n*[[Legal name]]\n*[[Married and maiden names]]\n*[[Matriname]]\n*[[Nickname]]\n*[[Pseudonym]]\n**[[Pen name]]\n**[[Stage name]]\n*[[Regnal name]]\n*[[Religious conversion]]\n*[[Witness protection]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Personal names}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Name Change}}\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Gender transitioning]]\n[[Category:Transgender law]]\n[[Category:Human names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Selfref|For information on altering your own Wikipedia username, see [[Wikipedia:Changing username]].}}\n{{for|name changes of places rather than persons|Geographical renaming}}\n[[File:Navneforandring.jpg|thumb|right|Name change certificate issued by [[Christian X of Denmark]] in 1917]]\n'''Name change''' generally refers to the legal act by a person of adopting a new name different from their name at birth, marriage or adoption.\n\nThe procedures and ease of a name change vary between jurisdictions. In general, [[common law]] jurisdictions have loose procedures for a name change while [[civil law (legal system)|civil law]] jurisdictions are more restrictive.\n\nA [[pseudonym]] is a name used in addition to the original or true name.  This does not require legal sanction. Pseudonyms are generally adopted to conceal a person's identity, but may also be used for personal, social or ideological reasons.\n\n==Reasons for changing one's name==\n* Marriage or civil partnership. \n* [[Divorce]] or [[Family estrangement|estrangement]] of parents.\n* To avoid a [[stalker]] or [[harassment]]\n* To choose a surname associated with a hobby, interest, or accomplishment (e.g., old name Henry Schifberg, new name [[Henry Lizardlover]])\n* To receive an inheritance conditional on adopting the name of the deceased (this reason was once quite common in landowning families in the UK)\n* To replace a frivolous name given by their parents (e.g., old name Mikey Maus, new name Marcus Maus)\n* To replace a name which might be considered undesirable with a more desirable one (e.g., old surname Lipschitz, new surname London)\n* To dissociate oneself from a former religion (e.g., Ahmed Abdullah to Adel Karim) \n* To dissociate themselves from a famous or infamous person (e.g., old name [[Michael Jackson]] new name Martin Jackson)\n* To identify with a famous or infamous person (e.g., old name Simon Johnson, new name Simon [[King Arthur|Pendragon]])\n* To dissociate themselves from a family [[Black sheep (term)|black sheep]] (e.g., relatives of [[Adolf Hitler]]).\n* To dissociate themselves from an ethnic origin (e.g., changing [[Battenberg family|Battenberg]] to [[Mountbatten]] or Jan Ludvik Hoch to [[Robert Maxwell]]).\n* To revert to a former name (e.g., [[Cynthia Lennon]], first wife of [[John Lennon]], after her divorce from later husband John Twist).\n* Commercial sponsorship (e.g., [[Jimmy White]] temporarily became Jimmy Brown for [[HP Sauce|HP brown sauce]],<ref name=\"BBCBrown1\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/funny_old_game/4245973.stm \"Jimmy Gets Saucy with Name Change\"], no by-line, ''BBC News'' (online edition), \"Sport: Fun and Games\" section, 8 February 2005; accessed 14 March 2007</ref> and [[Ashley Revell]] became Ashley blue square Revell for [[The Rank Group]]'s Blue Square service)\n* Protest or activism (e.g., old name Jennifer Taylor, new name Jennifer [[Environmentalism|Save the Forests]])\n* To change to a fictional character's name, (e.g., old name Tracy Darling, new name [[Tracy Beaker]])\n* To make their name more attractive or \"catchy\" so as to increase their chance of success (see [[Stage name]])\n* To change legal name to one used in everyday life (e.g., where middle name has been used throughout life)\n* To [[anglicise]] a name or choose a different name if one's name is too difficult to pronounce or spell for most people\n* To better fit one's [[gender identity]] as a [[transgender]] person (e.g., old name Bruce Jenner, new name [[Caitlyn Jenner]])\n\n==United States==\nIn the United States, [[State law (United States)|state law]]s regulate name changes. Several federal court rulings have set precedents regarding both court decreed name changes and [[common law]] name changes (changing the name at will), including ''[[Lindon v. First National Bank]]''.\n\nUsually a person can adopt any name desired for any reason. As of 2009, 46 states allow a person legally to change names by usage alone, with no paperwork, but a court order may be required for many institutions (such as banks or government institutions) to officially accept the change.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Julia Shear|last=Kushner|url=https://uclalawreview.org/pdf/57-1-7.pdf|title=The Right to Control One's Name|work=[[UCLA Law Review]]|issue=313|year=2009|pages=324\u20139}} The states which require a statutory name-change procedure are Hawaii, Louisiana, Maine, and Oklahoma.</ref>  Although the states ([[Law of Louisiana|except Louisiana]]) follow common law, there are differences in acceptable requirements; usually a [[court order]] is the most efficient way to change names (which would be applied for in a [[State court (United States)|state court]]), except at marriage, which has become a universally accepted reason for a name change.\n\nWhere a court process is used, it is necessary to [[pleading|plead]] that the name change is not for a [[fraud]]ulent or other illegal purpose, such as evading a [[lien]] or [[debt]] or for [[defamation|defaming]] someone else.  Applicants may be required to give a reasonable explanation for wanting to change their names. A fee is generally payable, and the applicant may be required to post legal notices in newspapers to announce the name change. Generally the judge has limited [[judicial discretion]] to deny a change of name: usually only if the name change is for fraudulent, frivolous or [[Morality|immoral]] purposes.<ref>Edward J. Bander, ''Change of Name and Law of Names'' (Dobbs Ferry, New York: Oceana Publications, 1973) Ch. 2&ndash;3.</ref>  In 2004, a [[Missouri]] man succeeded in changing his name to They.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/offbeat/2004-09-23-name-change_x.htm|work=USA Today|title=Missouri man legally changes his name to 'They'}}</ref> The [[Minnesota Supreme Court]] ruled that a name change to 1069 could be denied, but that Ten Sixty-Nine was acceptable (''Application of Dengler'', 1979); the [[North Dakota Supreme Court]] had denied the same request several years before (''Petition of Dengler'', 1976).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.court.state.nd.us/court/opinions/9205.htm|title=Petition of Dengler, 246 N.W.2d 758 (N.D. 1976)|work=state.nd.us}}</ref>\n\nIn nearly all states, a person cannot choose a name that is intended to mislead (such as adopting a celebrity's name), that is intentionally confusing, or that incites violence; nor can one adopt, as a name, a [[racial slur]], a threat, or an [[obscene|obscenity]].\n\nSome examples of typically allowed reasons for name changes in the U.S. include:\n* Adopting a new surname upon marriage (typically the surname of the spouse, a [[hyphenated name|hyphenated surname]], or some combination of parts of both surnames).  This is usually done without court proceedings.\n* Returning to the use of a prior surname (e.g., a [[maiden name]]) upon divorce.\n* Simplification or improved familiarity of spelling or pronunciation.\n\nUnder the federal immigration-and-nationality law, when aliens apply for [[naturalization]], they have the option of asking for their names to be changed upon the grants of citizenship with no additional fees. This allows them the opportunity to adopt more [[Cultural assimilation#Immigrant name changing as a form of assimilation|Americanized]] names.<ref>\"[http://www.uscis.gov/files/form/n-400.pdf N-400 Application for Naturalization]\", (US Citizenship and Immigration Services, 2011).</ref> During the naturalization interview, a petition for a name change is prepared to be forwarded to a [[United States federal courts|federal court]]. Applicants certify that they are not seeking a change of name for any unlawful purpose such as the avoidance of debt or evasion of [[Police|law enforcement]]. Such a name change would become final if within their jurisdiction, once a [[United States federal courts|federal court]] naturalizes an applicant.\n\nTo maintain a person's [[identity (social science)|identity]], it is desirable to obtain a formal order so there is continuity of personal records.\n\n===Informal methods of legal name change===\n\n====Assumed name====\nThe \"open and notorious\" use of a name is often sufficient to allow one to use an [[assumed name]]. In some jurisdictions, a trade name distinct from one's legal name can be registered with a county clerk, [[Secretary of State (U.S. state government)|secretary of state]], or other similar government authority. Persons who wish to publish materials and not to be associated with them may publish under [[pseudonym]]s; such a right is protected under [[case law]] pursuant to [[United States Constitution]].\n\n====Usage method====\nA common law name (i.e. one assumed without formality and for a non-fraudulent purpose) is a legal name.<ref>See, ''e.g.'', ''State v. Ford'', 172 P. 802; ''Bonnie Lee Daniels'', 337 A.2d 49; ''Elizabeth Marie Hauptly'' 312 N.E.2d 857; ''Piotrowski v. Piotrowski'', 247 N.W.2d 354; ''Thomas v. Thomas'', 427 N.E.2d 1009; ''Klein v. Klein'', 373 A.2d 86; ''Stuart v. Board of Elections'', 295 A.2d 223.</ref> In most states a statutory method, while quick and definitive, only supplements the common law method,<ref>''In Matter of Linda A.'', 480 N.Y.S.2d 996.</ref> unless the statute makes itself exclusive. Although a person may sue under a common law name.<ref>''Hoffman v. Bank of America'', (M.D. Florida 2006).</ref>\n\nIn [[California]] the \"usage method\" (changing the name at will under common law) is sufficient to change the name.  Not all jurisdictions require that the new name be used exclusively.<ref>For example, ''Kreuter v US'', 201 F2d 33 (true name need not be abandoned), Florida Statute 322.22 (driver's licenses in two names), ''Loser v. Plainfield'', 128 N.W. 1101 (Iowa), ''Ludwinska v John Hancock'', 317 Pa 577 (may be used for just one nonfraudulent transaction).</ref> Any fraudulent use or intent, such as changing the name to the same name as another person's name, may invalidate this type of name change.\n\nSpecifically in California, Code of Civil Procedure \u00a7 1279.5 and Family Code \u00a7 2082 regulate common law and court decreed name changes. Code of Civil Procedure \u00a7 1279.5 (a) reads, \"Except as provided in subdivision (b), (c), (d), or (e), nothing in this title shall be construed to abrogate the common law right of any person to change his or her name.\" Subdivisions b through e preclude one from changing their name by common law if they are in state prison, on probation, on parole, or have been convicted of a serious sex offense. If a person is not in any of these categories, then a common law name change is allowed. (Family Code \u00a7 2082 also contains some of the same wording.)\n\n====Preferred name====\nMany universities, hospitals, and other institutions allow one to use a \"preferred name\" instead of one's legal name.  This name can show up on class rosters, online learning platforms, and [[student ID]] cards.  It provides a \"transitional\"\nname change for those who have yet to, or cannot, receive a court-ordered name change.<ref name=\"UC Davis\">{{cite web|title=Preferred Name {{!}} Office of the University Registrar|url=https://registrar.ucdavis.edu/records/preferred-name.cfm|website=registrar.ucdavis.edu|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Leicester\">{{cite web|title=What is a preferred first name or preferred last name? \u2014 University of Leicester|url=http://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/hr/policies/ess/Questions/what-is-a-preferred-first-name-or-preferred-last-name|website=www2.le.ac.uk|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Official registration===\nA legal name change is merely the first step in the name-change process. A person must officially register the new name with the appropriate authorities whether the change was made as a result of a court order, marriage, divorce, adoption, or any of the other methods described above. The process includes notifying various government agencies, each of which may require legal proof of the name change and that may or may not charge a fee. Important government agencies to be notified include the [[Social Security Administration]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://faq.ssa.gov/link/portal/34011/34019/Article/3749/|title=How do I change or correct my name on my Social Security number card?|work=ssa.gov|access-date=2015-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102072805/https://faq.ssa.gov/link/portal/34011/34019/Article/3749/|archive-date=2016-01-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Bureau of Consular Affairs]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/passport/npic/agencies/agencies_913.html|title=U.S. Passports & International Travel|work=state.gov}}</ref> (for [[United States passport|passports]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fam.state.gov/FAM/08FAM/08FAM040301.html |title=8 FAM 403.1-4 Material Discrepancies (Major name changes) |last= |first= |date=August 7, 2018 |website=Foreign Affairs Manual |publisher=United States Department of State |access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> the [[Federal Communications Commission]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transition.fcc.gov/Forms/Form605/605.html|title=FCC Form 605|author=FCC Internet Services Staff|work=fcc.gov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422032207/http://transition.fcc.gov/Forms/Form605/605.html|archivedate=2014-04-22}}</ref> the [[Selective Service System]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sss.gov/regisrantsbk.htm#RegistrantObligations|title=Selective Service System: Registrant Obligations|website=www.sss.gov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329020540/http://www.sss.gov/regisrantsbk.htm#RegistrantObligations|archivedate=2015-03-29}}</ref> and the Department of Motor Vehicles (for a new driver's license, learner permit, state identification card, or vehicular registration). Additionally the new name must be registered with other institutions such as employers, banks, doctors, mortgage, insurance and credit card companies. Online services are available to assist in this process either through direct legal assistance or automated form processing.\n\nMost states require name changes to be registered with their departments of motor vehicles (DMVs) within a certain amount of time, and some state motor vehicle departments require updated social security cards to make changes, by first registering a new name with the Social Security office:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Several United States !! Time limits in days !! Notes\n|-\n|[[Arizona]] || 10 || Must appear in person with updated social security cards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://azdot.gov/motor-vehicles/driver-services/driver-license-information/change-your-address-or-name|title=Motor Vehicle Services|work=azdot.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Connecticut]] || Undefined || Must appear in person with updated social security cards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portal.ct.gov/DMV/Easy-Answers/Easy-Answers-Webpages/Change-of-Name|title=DMV Easy Answers for Change of Name|work=Department of Motor Vehicles}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Delaware]] || 30 || Must appear in person with updated social security cards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmv.de.gov/VehicleServices/titles/index.shtml?dc=ve_title_name|title=Requirements for Change of Name and Address|work=Division of Motor Vehicles|accessdate=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Illinois]] || 30 || <ref>[http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/rules_of_the_road/rr_chap01.html#changing_name_address] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070427004533/http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/rules_of_the_road/rr_chap01.html#changing_name_address|date=April 27, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Maryland]] || Undefined || Must appear in person<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mva.maryland.gov/drivers/apply/md-drivers-license.htm#mddlcorrecting|title=Maryland Driver's License: Correcting/Changing Your Maryland License or Permit|work=Motor Vehicle Administration}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[New Jersey]] || Undefined || Must appear in person<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.nj.us/mvc/drivertopics/namechange.htm|title=Name Change|work=New Jersey Motor Vehicle Commission}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[New York (state)|New York]] || Undefined || Must appear in person<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmv.ny.gov/dmvfaqs.htm#name|title=New York State DMV|work=New York State DMV|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626065446/http://www.dmv.ny.gov/dmvfaqs.htm#name|archivedate=2012-06-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[North Carolina]] || 60 || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdot.org/dmv/driver_services/drivershandbook/chapter1/renewalLicense.html#RDNameChanges|title=NCDOT: License and ID|work=[[North Carolina Department of Transportation]]|access-date=2007-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212202302/http://www.ncdot.org/dmv/driver_services/drivershandbook/chapter1/renewalLicense.html#RDNameChanges|archive-date=2007-12-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Pennsylvania]] || Undefined || Must appear in person for a driver's license or photo ID<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmv.pa.gov/Driver-Services/Driver-Licensing/Pages/Change-Your-Name-or-Address.aspx|title=Change Your Name or Address|work=DMV}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[South Carolina]] || 10 || <ref>http://www.scdmvonline.com/DMVNew/default.aspx?n=general_driver_license_information#NameorAddressChanges {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228092155/http://www.scdmvonline.com/DMVNew/default.aspx?n=general_driver_license_information |date=2012-12-28 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Texas]] || 30 || <ref>[http://www.txdps.state.tx.us/administration/driver_licensing_control/faq/answers_dl_id.htm#q18] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012023946/http://www.txdps.state.tx.us/administration/driver_licensing_control/faq/answers_dl_id.htm#q18|date=October 12, 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Vermont]] || 30 || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmv.vermont.gov/licenses/change-name-address|title=Change Address or Name on Your License \u2013 Department of Motor Vehicles|website=dmv.vermont.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wyoming]] || 10 || <ref>[http://dot.state.wy.us/Default.jsp?sCode=drvna] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070919202553/http://dot.state.wy.us/Default.jsp?sCode=drvna|date=September 19, 2007}}</ref>\n|}\nThe fees for registering a new name vary from state to state. The forms, along with the state-specific requirements, can generally be obtained for free.\n\nMany states will require reasons for wanting a name change. For example, in Florida, a court will not grant a petition for a change of name if it finds that (i) the petitioner has ulterior or illegal motives in seeking the name change, (ii) the petitioner's civil rights are suspended, or (iii) granting the name change will invade the property rights (''e.g.'', intellectual property rights) of others.<ref>see, e.g., [http://abcfamilylaw.com/practice-areas/change-of-name www.abcfamilylaw.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128015829/http://www.abcfamilylaw.com/practice-areas/change-of-name |date=2010-11-28 }}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\nIn the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland]], citizens and residents have the freedom to change their names with relative ease.\n\nIn theory, anyone who is at least 16 and resident in the United Kingdom can call themselves whatever they wish. However, over the past hundred years or so, formal procedures that are recognized by record holders such as government departments, companies and organizations have evolved, which enable a citizen legally to change the name recorded on their [[passport]], [[driving licence]], tax and [[National Insurance]] records, bank and credit cards, etc., provided that \"documentary evidence\" of a change of name is provided. Documents such as [[birth certificate|birth]], [[marriage certificate|marriage]] and educational certificates cannot be changed because these documents are \"matters of fact\", which means that they were correct at the time they were issued.\n\nDocumentary evidence of a change of name can be in a number of forms, such as a marriage certificate, [[decree absolute]], civil partnership certificate, [[statutory declaration]] or [[deed of change of name]]. Such documents are mere evidence that a change of name has occurred, however, and they do not themselves operate to change a person's name. Deeds of change of name are by far the most commonly used method of providing evidence of a change of name other than changing a woman's surname after marriage. A deed poll is a legal document that binds a single person to a particular course of action (in this case, changing one's name for all purposes). The term 'deed' is common to signed, written agreements that have been shown to all concerned parties. Strictly speaking, it is not a contract because it binds only one party and expresses an intention instead of a promise. 'Poll' is an old legal term referring to official documents that had cut edges (were polled) so that they were straight.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/files/deedpolls_notes_0308.doc ''Enrolling a Name Change in the Royal Courts of Justice''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002143613/http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/files/deedpolls_notes_0308.doc |date=2008-10-02 }} (March 2008). Her Majesty's Courts Service. Retrieved September 12, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/9805.htm#deed_polls ''Judgement and Orders Section''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606115033/http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/9805.htm |date=2011-06-06 }}(March 26, 2008). Her Majesty's Courts Service. \u00a7 Deed Polls. Retrieved September 12, 2008.</ref>\n\n===England and Wales===\nPeople whose births are registered in England and Wales may have their [[deed poll]] enrolled at the [[Royal Courts of Justice]] in [[London]].<ref>[https://deedpolloffice.com/pdf/phillimore_and_fry_index.pdf www.deedpolloffice.com]</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> See also [[College of Arms#Change of names]].\n\n====Historical usage====\n{{See also|Double-barrelled name#British tradition}}\nFrom the medi\u00e6val age to the 19th century, the era of family dynasties, name changes were frequently demanded of heirs in the last wills and testaments, legacies and bequests, of members of the gentry and nobility who were the last males of their bloodline. Such persons frequently selected a younger nephew or cousin as the heir to their estates on condition that he should adopt the surname and armorials of the legator in lieu of his patronymic. Thus the ancient family otherwise destined to extinction would appear to continue as a great dynasty in the making. Such changes were also more rarely demanded by [[marriage settlement]]s, for example where the father of a sole daughter and heiress demanded that as a condition of his daughter's [[dowry]] her husband should adopt his father-in-law's surname and arms. Thus the progeny of the marriage would continue the otherwise extinct family's name. Such name changes were generally only demanded of younger sons, where an elder brother was available to inherit the paternal estates under primogeniture and carry on the name and arms abandoned by the younger brother. Such name changes were effected by obtaining a private [[Act of Parliament]] or by obtaining a [[College of Arms|Royal Licence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deedpolloffice.com/research#royal-licences|title=Researching a past change of name \u2013 D\u2022P\u2022O|work=Deed Poll Office}}</ref> A less radical procedure adopted from the 18th century onwards was for the legator or settlor to demand only that the legatee or beneficiary should adopt his surname ''in addition to'' his patronymic, not in place of it, which gave rise to the \"[[Double-barrelled name|double-barrelled]]\", even the \"triple-barrelled\" name, frequently parodied in literature as epitomising the wealthy \"[[squirearchy]]\" with an embarrassment of inherited estates.\n\nWell known examples are:\n*Russell to Gorges (14th century). Ralph IV Gorges, 2nd Baron Gorges, died without issue in 1331. In an effort to preserve his family name and arms he made one of his younger nephews his heir, on condition that he should adopt the name and arms of Gorges. This nephew was William Russell, the second son of his second sister Eleanor de Gorges who had married Sir Theobald Russell (d.1341) of [[Kingston Russell]], Dorset. The event is referred to in one of the earliest heraldic law cases brought concerning English armory, [[Warbelton v. Gorges]] in 1347.\n*Smithson to Percy (18th century). [[Hugh Percy, 1st Duke of Northumberland|Sir Hugh Smithson, 4th Baronet]] (1715\u20131786) (c.1714\u20131786) in 1740 married [[Elizabeth Percy, Duchess of Northumberland|Lady Elizabeth Seymour]], daughter and sole heiress of [[Algernon Seymour, 7th Duke of Somerset]], and granddaughter of Lady Elizabeth Percy (d.1722), daughter and sole heiress of [[Josceline Percy, 11th Earl of Northumberland]] (1644\u20131670). In 1740, by a private Act of Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deedpolloffice.com/research/private-acts-parliament/1749-23-Geo-2-14|title=Hugh Earl of Northumberland's name and arms. \u2013 D\u2022P\u2022O|work=Deed Poll Office}}</ref> Smithson changed his surname to Percy and inherited the title [[Earl of Northumberland]] and was later created [[Duke of Northumberland]].\n\n===Scotland===\nPeople whose births are [[civil registration|registered]] in Scotland (or who were adopted in Scotland) can change their name in the same way as people from the rest of the United Kingdom.  However they can optionally apply to the [[Registrar General for Scotland]] to have their birth certificate amended to show the new name and have the respective register updated.\n\n==Other common law countries==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIndividuals may legally change their name through the [[States and territories of Australia|state and territory]] governments of Australia according to state or territory laws and regulations via agencies generally titled \"Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australia.gov.au/information-and-services/family-and-community/births-deaths-and-marriages-registries|title=Births, deaths and marriages registries \u2013 australia.gov.au|first=Digital Transformation|last=Agency|website=www.australia.gov.au}}</ref>  Exceptions exist for some states such as restricted persons (e.g. jail inmate)<ref>http://www.bdm.nsw.gov.au/Pages/change-of-name/change-of-name.aspx</ref> and in some states, changes may only be made once a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qld.gov.au/law/births-deaths-marriages-and-divorces/changing-your-name/changing-your-name/|title=Changing your name \u2013 Your rights, crime and the law|first=; c=AU; o=The State of Queensland; ou=Communication Services|last=Branch|website=www.qld.gov.au}}</ref>\n\nInstitutions such as banks,<ref>http://www.austrac.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/cip_form_ind_mar08.pdf</ref> the Passports Office<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.passports.gov.au/passportsexplained/theapplicationprocess/eligibilityoverview/Pages/confirmingidentity.aspx|title=Documents that confirm your Australian citizenship and identity|first=Australian Passports|last=Office|website=www.passports.gov.au}}</ref> and transport authorities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transport.wa.gov.au/licensing/change-my-name.asp|title=Change my name|first=|last=nw|website=www.transport.wa.gov.au}}</ref> require proof of identity, so people who change their names need to have proof of the change.\n\nIf a person's birth or adoption was registered in Australia, the change will also be noted (in most cases) on the person's birth or adoption registration, and in some states or territories, the name change can be evidenced either through a re-issued [[Birth certificate#Australia|birth certificate]] if born in Australia and/or \"Change of Name Certificate\".  These certificates are recognised secure [[Identity documents of Australia|identity documents]] and can be verified electronically through the [[Attorney-general of Australia]]'s Document Verification Service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx|title=Document Verification Service|first=Attorney-General's|last=Department|website=www.ag.gov.au|access-date=2017-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321081501/https://www.ag.gov.au/RightsAndProtections/IdentitySecurity/Pages/DocumentVerificationService.aspx|archive-date=2017-03-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{Australian Identity Documents}}\n\n===Canada===\nAll Canadian provinces and territories except Quebec allow their residents, whether Citizens, Permanent Residents or Temporary Residents, to obtain a name change, provided they fulfil the pertinent regulations (e.g. time lived in province) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ccla.org/frequently-asked-questions-regarding-change-of-name-for-trans-persons/|title=Frequently Asked Questions Regarding Change of Name for Trans Persons|date=2015-05-19|website=Canadian Civil Liberties Association|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>. Quebec, being a civil law jurisdiction, has substantial differences from the rest of Canada in how it permits its residents to obtain a change of name; further information is available in the Quebec section of the article.\n\n===Hong Kong===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2010}}\nIt is a common practice for ethnic Chinese residents of Hong Kong to adopt a western-style English name in addition to their transliterated Chinese name. As they often adopt western-style English names after being registered on the birth register, the fact that they want to include a western-style English name as part of their [[Legal name|legal English name]] is regarded as a name change which usually requires a deed poll.\n\nHowever, the [[Immigration Department (Hong Kong)|Immigration Department]] which is responsible for processing applications for name change allows applicants to submit such applications without deeds poll; anyone who has a phonetic English name only and wishes to include a western-style English name as part of his or her legal English name can apply to the Immigration Department without a deed poll. Only one application of this kind is allowed for each applicant; any application for subsequent change(s) must be made with a deed poll.\n\n===Ireland===\nIn the [[Republic of Ireland]], a person earns their name by \"use and repute\".<ref name=\"citizensinformation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensinformation.ie/en/birth_family_relationships/problems_in_marriages_and_other_relationships/changing_your_name_by_deed_poll.html|title=Changing your name by deed poll|website=www.citizensinformation.ie}}</ref> For most purposes it is enough to simply use the desired name and ask others to call you by that name.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> This was the traditional practice for a bride adopting her husband's surname.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> A [[deed of change of name|change of name deed poll]] is not required, but provides documentary evidence of a name change.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> Resident non-[[Citizenship of the European Union|EU nationals]] must apply to the [[Irish Naturalisation and Immigration Service]] for a deed poll.<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> The deed poll requires a witness [[affidavit]], and may optionally be enrolled in the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] upon payment of [[stamp duty]].<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> An enrolled deed poll is required for some administrative name changes, such as on a [[Driving licence in the Republic of Ireland|driving licence]]<ref name=\"citizensinformation\"/> or when [[Transgender rights in Ireland|changing legal gender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensinformation.ie/en/birth_family_relationships/changing_to_your_preferred_gender.html|title=Changing to your preferred gender|website=www.citizensinformation.ie}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\nFrom September 1995, [[New Zealanders]] can change their name by making a [[statutory declaration]] and, if approved, the new name is registered with the Births, Deaths and Marriages section of the Department of Internal Affairs (Identity Services). Prior to September 1995, they changed their name by [[deed poll]].<ref>[http://www.dia.govt.nz/diawebsite.nsf/Files/EOIStandard/$file/EOIStandard.pdf Evidence of Identity Standard] NZ Department of Internal Affairs, June 2006, Version 1.0, {{ISBN|0-478-24462-2}}, page 123</ref>\n\n==Civil law==\nIn general, unlike in [[common law]] countries, names cannot be changed at will in [[civil law (legal system)|civil law]] jurisdictions. Usually, a name change requires government approval and is only rarely granted, though legal name changes have become more common in some jurisdictions over the last years. The reason given for this system is usually the public interest in the unique identifiability of a person, e.g., in governmental registers, although with the advent of [[personal identification numbers]], that rationale may be in need of reconsideration.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n\n===Belgium===\nChanges in law Aug 2018 changes first name and fee will fall under the authority of local town hall <ref>https://justitie.belgium.be/nl/nieuws/persberichten_70</ref> In Belgian law, a name is in principle considered fixed for life, but under exceptional circumstances, a person may apply to the Ministry of Justice for a name change. This requires a Royal Decree (French: ''Arr\u00eat\u00e9 royal'', Dutch: ''Koninklijk besluit'') for last names, but only a Ministerial Decree for first names. The new name must not cause confusion or cause damage to the bearer or others. Examples of requests that are usually considered favorably:\n* A person of non-European origin who wants to adopt a less exotic name to further his/her integration in Belgian society\n* A person stuck with a ridiculous last name that is causing him/her great embarrassment or emotional distress. Actual examples: Salami, Naaktgeboren (\"born naked\"), and Clooten (\"sods of earth\" in Middle Dutch, but \"testicles\" in modern Dutch)\n* (for minor children) following legal adoption or recognition of paternity<ref>[http://www.just.fgov.be/nl_htm/informatie/htm_justitie_atotz/naamveranderen.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514153237/http://www.just.fgov.be/nl_htm/informatie/htm_justitie_atotz/naamveranderen.html|date=May 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Brazil===\nAccording to the Brazilian Civil Code and the Public Registries Act, the name registered after birth is definitive and immutable. However, there are some circumstances under which a name change is allowed: \n* If an obvious writing error is made while registering the name of the child.  \n* In the first year after a person reaches the [[age of majority]] (18&nbsp;years), they can request a change in their first names, but modification of surnames is not allowed.  \n* If a person's name exposes them to ridicule and harms their everyday well-being.  \n* If a person is recognized publicly by another name, they can request a name change or addition, by providing as support three testimonials of the change in name.  \n* If a person has undergone a sex change, recent jurisprudence has allowed name modifications in most such cases.\n\n===India===\nIn India, the person concerned submits a name change request to an appropriate authority, with supporting documents. Subsequently, an application must be made to the Government Printing Press, which issues an Official Gazette Notification certifying the change of name.<ref>http://goaprintingpress.gov.in/uploads/Change%20of%20Name%20and%20Surname%20Act.pdf</ref>\n\n===Norway===\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2012}}\nAlthough it has always been relatively easy to change one's legal names in Norway, it used to require some kind of government approval. As late as 1830, local vicars were instructed to write both given (Christian) names, as well as last names, in the baptismal record. Earlier, only the given name of the child, birth date, baptismal date, and sex were written down, alongside the parents' names. It was not until the beginning of the 20th century, however, that the authorities required everyone to adopt a family surname. Until about 1980, the government still required that a name change applicant apply to the government regional representative (fylkesmann). The law has been replaced twice since then. Nowadays, the process is as easy as in common-law countries; the subject merely submits the names wanted (providing that the surname chosen is not in use or is not used by fewer than 200 persons) to the local authorities for the purposes of election rosters and census counts; there is no longer an application process.\n\n===Philippines===\n2001 RA 9048 amends Articles 376 and 412 of the [[Civil Code of the Philippines]], which prohibit the change of name or surname of a person, or any correction or change of entry in a civil register without a judicial order. Administrative Order No. 1 Series of 2001, implemented the law.<ref>[https://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/irr_ra9048.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621060551/http://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/irr_ra9048.html|date=June 21, 2008}}</ref> It authorizes the city or municipal civil registrar or the consul general to correct a clerical or typographical error in an entry or change the first name or nickname in the civil register without need of a judicial order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/primerra9048.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212183553/http://www.census.gov.ph/data/civilreg/primerra9048.html|archivedate=February 12, 2012|website=census.gov.ph|title= Civil Registration \u2013 Primer for RA 9048}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicactno9048.htm|title=PHILIPPINE LAWS, STATUTES AND CODES \u2013 CHAN ROBLES VIRTUAL LAW LIBRARY|work=chanrobles.com}}</ref>\n\n====Name and gender change====\nIn case of controversial and substantial changes, [[Philippines]] [[jurisprudence]] requires full-blown court [[lawsuit]], that must include the local civil registrar in the petition, since RA 9048 and Rule 108 (Cancellation or correction of entries in the Civil Registry) of the Rules of Court do not allow the change of sex in a birth certificate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/rulesofcourtspecialproceedings.htm#RULE%20108|title=SPECIAL PROCEEDINGS|work=chanrobles.com}}</ref>\n\nThe only landmark case in the Philippines on name and legal sex change is the Jeff Cagandahan case. The [[Supreme Court of the Philippines]] Justice [[Leonardo Quisumbing]] on September 12, 2008, allowed Cagandahan, 27, who has [[congenital adrenal hyperplasia]], to change his [[birth certificate]] name from Jennifer to Jeff, and his legal gender from female to male.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080917-161148/Call-him-Jeff-says-SC-he-used-to-be-called-Jennifer|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808193038/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20080917-161148/Call-him-Jeff-says-SC-he-used-to-be-called-Jennifer|archivedate=August 8, 2014|title=Call him Jeff, says SC; he used to be called Jennifer|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,24359150-401,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216041937/http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,24359150-401,00.html|archivedate=February 16, 2009|title=Woman's body 'naturally' became male|work=[[News.com.au]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,423242,00.html|title=Rare Condition Turns Woman Into Man|work=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n===Quebec===\nIn Quebec, only Citizens may obtain a change of name from the Directeur de l'Etat Civil. Permanent Residents residing in Quebec, if falling under an [[Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada]] exception, may make a statutory declaration to IRCC and obtain a change of name through them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship/corporate/publications-manuals/operational-bulletins-manuals/identity-management/exceptions.html|title=Exceptions to change of name requirements|last=Immigration|first=Refugees and Citizenship Canada|date=2017-11-16|website=aem|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> Otherwise, as with all Temporary Residents residing in Quebec, they must obtain a change of name from the country that issued their passport/travel document.\n\nQuebec also has other strict regulations regarding name changes. For example, Micheline Montreuil, a trans woman who is non-operative, had to undergo a lengthy process to have her name legally changed. Initially, the Directeur de l'Etat Civil refused to permit the change on the grounds that someone legally assigned male at birth could not bear a female name. According to Quebec law, Montreuil could not change her record of sex because this requires proof of a completed [[sex reassignment surgery]], which she has not had. On November 1, 1999, the provincial court of appeals ruled that nothing in the law prevented a person who was legally male from legally adopting a woman's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.micheline.ca/page034-batailles-e.htm#dictateur|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212004926/http://www.micheline.ca/page034-batailles-e.htm|archivedate=February 12, 2012|title=Micheline Anne H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Montreuil and his fights|website=micheline.ca}}</ref> Another issue specific to Quebec is married names. Because of the [[Quebec Charter of Rights]], married women in Quebec have been unable to adopt their spouse's surname since 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3940094/maiden-married-names-countries/|title=Here Are Places Women Can't Take Their Husband's Name When They Get Married|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> Other provinces allow their residents to change their last name on the strength of their [[Marriage certificate|marriage certificate.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.programs.alberta.ca/Living/5962.aspx?Ns=364+6228&N=770|title=Government of Alberta \u2013 Programs and Services \u2013 Getting Married|author=Government of Alberta|work=alberta.ca}}</ref>\n\nThe Directeur de l'Etat Civil will amend a Quebec birth certificate if a name change certificate is issued by another province. Some have used that loophole to legally change their names by temporarily moving another Canadian province or territory, which follow more permissive common-law rules.\n\n===South Africa===\nSouth Africa, which uses a mixture of common law and civil [[Roman Dutch law]], mostly uses common-law procedures with regard to name change. Name changes in [[South Africa]] are regulated by the Births and Deaths Registration Act (Act 51 of 1992, as amended). The personal information of all citizens and permanent residents is recorded on the Population Register, so any name changes must be registered.\n\nA person can change their forenames by submitting a form to the [[South African Department of Home Affairs|Department of Home Affairs]]. An individual's surname, or that of a family, may be changed by applying to the Department and providing a \"good and sufficient reason\" for the change.\n\nA married woman can change her surname to that of her husband or join her maiden name with her husband's surname, and a divorced woman may return to her previous surname, without applying or paying a fee; but she must notify the department so that the details in the Population Register can be changed. (It is possible that, if challenged, these provisions might be held to be unconstitutional because they apply only to women.)\n\nSouth Africa has officially recognized same sex marriages since 2006 and in doing so now allows one or both partners to change their surnames in the marriage register on the day of the marriage. A new passport and ID book can then be applied for with the new married surname as well.\n\nThe surnames of minor children can also be changed under various circumstances involving the marriage, divorce or death of a parent, children born out of wedlock, and guardianship.<ref>[http://www.home-affairs.gov.za/personal_amendments.asp ''Personal Amendments.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911222143/http://www.home-affairs.gov.za/personal_amendments.asp |date=2008-09-11 }} (c. 1997). South African Department of Home Affairs. Retrieved May 19, 2010</ref>\n\n===Switzerland===\nIn Switzerland, a name change requires the approval of the respective [[Cantons of Switzerland|Cantonal]] government, if there are important reasons (''wichtige Gr\u00fcnde'' / ''justes motifs'') for the change, according to article 30 of the [[Swiss Civil Code]]. When aliens apply for naturalization, they have the option of asking for their names to be changed upon the grants of citizenship with no additional fees.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} According to the case law of the [[Swiss Federal Supreme Court]], such requests must be granted only if the petitioner shows that they suffer substantially from their present name, e.g., if it is the same as that of a notorious criminal.\n\n===Taiwan===\n{{Wikibooks|Annotated Republic of China Laws/Name Act}}\nIn [[Taiwan]], the ''Name Act'' bans changing one's legal name for some criminal reasons per [https://law.moj.gov.tw/ENG/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=D0030011&norge=6 Article 15] since 2015 (Article 12 since 2001). Otherwise, one may change the surname, given name, or both per Article 8, 9, or 10 since 2015 (Article 5, 6, or 7 since 1953, or Article 6, 7, or 8 since 2001).\n\nChanging the given name is allowed if:<ref>Article 6 of the ''Name Act'' (1953) ([[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b42\u5e74)]]), amended into Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001) ([[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b90\u5e74)]]), then amended into Article 9 of the ''Name Act'' (2015) [[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b104\u5e74)]].</ref>\n#Having the same name when serving or studying in the same institution or school.\n#Since 1983, having the same given name as one's parent, grandparent, or great-grandparent.<ref>Clause 2 of Article 6 of the ''Name Act'' (1983) ([[s:zh:\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b72\u5e74)|\u59d3\u540d\u689d\u4f8b (\u6c11\u570b72\u5e74)]]), amended into Clause 2 of Section 1 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), then amended into Clause 2 of Section 1 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref>\n#Having the same name as someone else who lives in the same county or city and having lived there for at least 6 months.\n#Having the same name as a wanted criminal, for example [[:zh:\u9673\u9032\u8208|\u9673\u9032\u8208 (Ch\u00e9n J\u00ecnx\u012bng)]], a common name used by not only a convicted kidnapper and murderer who was executed in Taiwan for major crimes in 1997 ([[:zh:\u9673\u9032\u8208 (\u53f0\u7063\u7f6a\u72af)]]) but also a Taiwanese statesman ([[:zh:\u9673\u9032\u8208 (\u53f0\u7063\u653f\u6cbb\u4eba\u7269)]]).\n#Since 2015, acknowledgement by father or adoption starts or ends.\n#Having special reasons,<ref>Clause 6 of Section 1 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), amended into Clause 6 of Section 1 of Article 9 of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref> which is limited to thrice since 2015 (twice since 2001) in one's lifetime, while the second given name change of this type requires the age of majority.<ref>Section 2 of Article 7 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), amended into Section 2 of Article 9 of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref>\n\n====Replacing documents====\nDiplomas, work experience documents, licenses, permits, and other such documents shall use a person\u2019s legal name to avoid being deemed invalid<ref>Article 3 of the ''Name Act'' (1953), amended into Article 4 of the ''Name Act'' (2001), then amended into [https://law.moj.gov.tw/ENG/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=D0030011&norge=6 Article 6] of the ''Name Act'' (2015).</ref>, so those intending to change names have to note that:\n\nLicensed Taiwanese driver who legally changes the name without reporting to the competent traffic authority is fined 300 to 600 [[new Taiwan dollar]]s and asked to re-register the legal name.<ref>[https://law.moj.gov.tw/ENG/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=K0040012&norge=25 Article 25] of the ''Road Traffic Management and Penalty Act'' amended in 1986 and effective on 1 January 1987, having increased the administrative fine from 30 to 150 new Taiwan dollars effective on 1 May 1968 per \nClause 1 of Article 31 of the same ''Act'', and 150 to 300 new Taiwan dollars per Article 25 of the amendment in 1975 effective on 1 January 1976.</ref>\n{{Wikibooks|Annotated Republic of China Laws/Passport Act/2015}}\n[[Taiwan passport#Data page|Taiwan passports]] are to be replaced after having changed the names.<ref>Clause 3 of Section 1 of Article 19 of the ''Passport Act'' fully amended in 2015 effective on 1 January 2016, from Clause 3 of Section 1 of Article 15 of the ''Passport Act'' effective on 21 May 2000.</ref>\n\nRegistration of change in name of the right holder having been changed after a land right has been registered, shall be applied; the same shall apply to the change of the name of administrator.<ref>Section 1 of [https://law.moj.gov.tw/LawClass/LawSearchContent.aspx?pcode=D0060003&norge=149 Article 149] of the ''Regulations of The Land Registration''</ref>\n\n====Overseas application====\n{{Wikibooks|Annotated Republic of China Regulations/Enforcement Rules of the Name Act}}\nA [[national without household registration]] may apply for name change outside Taiwan at a [[List of diplomatic missions of Taiwan|Taiwanese diplomatic mission]], but having had [[household registration in Taiwan]] may apply there only to forward a name change application to the Household Registration Office covering the last Taiwanese address of residency<ref>The last Section of Article 4 of the ''Enforcement Rules of the Name Act'' since 2001.</ref>, which is a better method only if no risk of discrepancies among Taiwanese documents, so anyone having considerable Taiwanese documents should still change the name in person at Taiwanese Household Registration Office, to also replace the [[National Identification Card (Republic of China)|National Identification Card]], [[Healthcare in Taiwan|healthcard card]], driver license, etc.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boca.gov.tw/cp-24-145-2695c-1.html |title=\u570b\u5916\u7533\u8acb\u8b77\u7167\u76f8\u95dc\u8cc7\u8a0a\uff1a\u4e00\u822c\u4eba\u6c11\u63db\u767c |last= |first= |date=2019-10-28 |website= |publisher=[[Bureau of Consular Affairs (Republic of China)]] |access-date=2019-11-22 |language=zh-hant|quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Name change on religious conversion==\n{{further|Religious name}}\nAdherents of various religions change their name upon [[Religious conversion|conversion]] or confirmation. The name adopted may not have any legal status but will represent their adopted religious beliefs.<ref>Celia Emmelhainz, [http://works.bepress.com/emmelhainz/4/ ''Naming a New Self: Identity Elasticity and Self-Definition in Voluntary Name Changes.''] (c. 2012). Names, Vol. 60, Iss. 3. Retrieved April 4, 2016</ref>\n\n===Buddhism===\n* Individuals who attend a ceremony to officially become Buddhists are usually given a new \"[[Dharma name]]\", which marks their \"[[Refuge (Buddhism)|taking refuge]]\".\n\n===Christianity===\n* It has been historical Christian practice to adopt a name on [[baptism]] or (in some countries) [[confirmation (sacrament)|confirmation]].<ref>[http://www.catholic-forum.com/saints/ce001006.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050428082432/http://www.catholic-forum.com/saints/ce001006.htm|date=April 28, 2005}}</ref>\n* The customary practice whereby persons entering a [[religious institute]] take on a [[name in religion]] is still observed by [[Eastern Orthodox]] and some traditional [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]]. Eastern Orthodox monastics are usually given the name of a prophet or a monastic saint.\n* [[Pope]]s take a [[papal name]] upon their accession to office; for example, [[Jorge M. Bergoglio]] adopted the name [[Francis (given name)|Francis]].\n\n===Hinduism===\nThere is no formal concept of conversion in Hinduism but converts to Hinduism are accepted, usually after a small ceremony called [[Shuddhi|Shudhikaran]] (purification). Individuals who attend a Shudhikaran ceremony to officially become [[Hindu]] may be optionally given a new [[Dharma]] (religious) name, which is usually based on [[Sanskrit]] or [[Indian name]] such as names based on [[Hindu deities]].\n\n===Islam===\n* Converts to Islamic faith may choose a new name; although it is not required, it may in some cases be preferable for personal reasons or because the name is of uncertain Islamicity (e.g. the person converting has a [[theophoric name]] in another religion, such as Christopher or Ganesh). Boxer Cassius Clay's adoption of the name [[Muhammad Ali]] is a well-known example, as is Cat Stevens' change to [[Yusuf Islam]] and Malcolm Little's adoption of the name [[Malcolm X]] and later ''El-Hajj Malik El-Shabazz''.  On the other hand, converts may choose to keep their names, as did [[Dave Chappelle]].\n*Women do not normally take their husbands' surnames as their own. Their maiden name continues to be their surname even after marriage. Sometimes their husbands first name becomes their surname, similar to the case of surname chains indicating someone's chain of fathers. \n* In Islamic tradition, there are two kinds of [[surname]].\n:# The first kind comes from the father's first name, which means that the particular person is the child of. For example, a name such as ''ibn Abdullah'' means \"son of Abdullah\", or ''bint Abdullah'' means \"daughter of Abdullah\". Father descendant names can be chained, meaning that an individual can have the name of their father, followed by their paternal grandfather, followed by the father of that grandfather, to indicate a patrilineal lineage.\n:# The second kind is associated with [[clan]], [[tribal]] or [[ethnic]] affiliation and is also solely dependant on the person's patrilineal line. In Islamic family law, the individual is required to keep the clan, tribal or ethnic affiliation of their father where it is known, whether the child be illegitimate, staying with their mother after divorce or adopted.\nThe last name cannot be changed in such a way as to reflect a heritage that is not that of one's biological father.\n\n===Judaism===\n* Jewish people in the Diaspora sometimes give their children two names: a secular name for everyday use and a Hebrew name for religious purposes.  [[Conversion to Judaism|Converts to Judaism]] choose a Hebrew name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://judaism.about.com/library/3_lifecycles/names/bl_names.htm|title=Choosing a Hebrew Name \u2013 Naming a Jewish Baby|author=Ariela Pelaia|work=About.com Religion & Spirituality}}</ref> Full Jewish names include a [[patronym]]: converts take the patronym \"ben/bat Avraham Avinu\" (son/daughter of Our Father Abraham) as converts are held to be spiritual descendants of [[Abraham]], the forebear of Jews.\n\n===Sikhism===\n* Those in the [[Sikh]] faith adopt a new last name upon baptism into the [[Khalsa]]. Men adopt the last name [[Singh]], while women adopt the last name [[Kaur]].\n* The Sikhs adopted the name Singh in 1699 during the Birth of the Khalsa.\n\n===Wicca===\n* Some [[Wiccans]] have a [[craft name]] that is used during coven gatherings and rituals.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Family name]], including patrilineal surnames\n*[[Given name]]\n*[[Hornsleth Village Project]]\n*[[In re McUlta]]\n*[[Legal aspects of transsexualism]] for information about name change for transgender and transsexual people\n**[[Diane Marie Rodriguez Zambrano]], an activist who sued to enable legal name change in Ecuador for purposes of [[gender identity]]\n*[[Legal name]]\n*[[Married and maiden names]]\n*[[Matriname]]\n*[[Nickname]]\n*[[Pseudonym]]\n**[[Pen name]]\n**[[Stage name]]\n*[[Regnal name]]\n*[[Religious conversion]]\n*[[Witness protection]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Personal names}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Name Change}}\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Gender transitioning]]\n[[Category:Transgender law]]\n[[Category:Human names]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4062:84:bda7::1a29:60a5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(My problem)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Name_change"}
{"title_page": "Charlie Heaton", "text_new": "{{short description|British actor and musician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Charlie Heaton\n| image        = CharlieHeaton2017.jpg\n| caption      = Heaton in 2017\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 6 February 1994 (age 26) \n| birth_place  = [[Leeds, West Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   = Actor, musician\n| years_active = 2012\u2013present\n| children     = 1 son\n| known_for    = ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n}}\n\n'''Charlie R. Heaton''' (born 6 February 1994) is an English actor and musician.<ref name=\"interviewmag\">{{Cite journal|last=Dziautaite|first=Modesta|date=18 July 2016|editor-last=Bailey|editor-first=David|title=Charlie Heaton|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/charlie-heaton#_|access-date=31 July 2016|magazine=[[Interview Magazine]]}}</ref> He is best known for playing Jonathan Byers in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Stranger Things]]'' and [[Cannonball (comics)|Sam Guthrie/Cannonball]] in the 2020 superhero horror film ''[[The New Mutants (film)|The New Mutants]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHeaton was born in [[Leeds]]<ref>{{cite video |title=Stranger Things' Charlie Heaton and Natalia Dyer Take A Lie Detector Test |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m_-N3bOJTQk |work=Vanity Fair |date=12 July 2019}}</ref> and raised on a [[council estate]] in [[Bridlington]] by his mother. he went to school at Bridlington Secondary School<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weinstock |first1=Tish |title=stranger things have happened: charlie heaton on finding fame |url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/gyqpdy/stranger-things-have-happened-charlie-heaton-on-finding-fame |work=I-D Vice |date=2 November 2016}}</ref> After moving to London when he was 16, Heaton joined London [[noise-rock]] band Comanechi as the drummer and toured with them for more than a year.<ref name=\"interviewmag\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/stars-of-tomorrow/charlie-heaton-stars-of-tomorrow-2015/5094630.article|title=Charlie Heaton, Stars of Tomorrow 2015|last=Grater|first=Tom|date=5 October 2015|work=[[Screen Daily]]|publisher=Media Business Insight Limited|access-date=31 July 2016}}</ref> He also went on to play with [[The Quietus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/tv-film/features/charlie-heaton/band-name/|title=What is the name of Charlie Heaton\u2019s band?|website=PopBuzz|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> Heaton then joined London-based [[Psychedelic rock|psychedelic]] band Half Loon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BNPqOHABrHY/|title=Charlie Heaton on Instagram: \"Hey guys! 'Half loon' the band I used to play in debuted their first single 'Ruth' from their upcoming album. Go to there page to check it\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2014, Heaton played a role in a short film named \"[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9217058/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_14 Life Needs Courage]\". In 2015, he made his acting debut with the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] crime drama series ''[[DCI Banks]]'', playing the role of Gary McCready.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Jennifer|title=DCI BANKS: Season 4|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2015/apr/23/dci-banks-season-4/|accessdate=3 September 2015|work=KPBS.org|date=23 April 2015}}</ref> He then appeared as Riley in [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s detective series ''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vera Cast List 2015: ITV Series 5 Air Date and Character Details|url=http://tellychat.co.uk/vera-series-5-itv-2015-starts-filming-vera-stanhope-new-episodes-0445|website=TellyChat.co.uk|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> He guest-starred in [[BBC One]]'s medical drama series ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' as Jason Waycott.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Department of Secrets \u2013 Series 29 Episode 31 of 46|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b05tqxbb|publisher=BBC|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> In 2016, he appeared in the thriller film ''[[Shut In (2016 film)|Shut In]]'', co-starring [[Naomi Watts]] and [[Oliver Platt]], and directed by [[Farren Blackburn]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Hipes|first1=Patrick|title=Oliver Platt Joins Naomi Watts In 'Shut In' For EuropaCorp & Lava Bear|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/oliver-platt-shut-in-movie-naomi-watts-1201394566|accessdate=3 September 2015|magazine=Deadline.com|date=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Naomi Watts' ''Shut In'' Set 2016 Release Date|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/naomi-watts-shut-in-sullivan-stapletons-the-lake-set-2016-release-dates-1201448033|accessdate=3 September 2015|website=Variety|date=6 March 2015}}</ref> Heaton also plays Jonathan Byers in the [[Netflix]] supernatural drama series ''[[Stranger Things (TV series)|Stranger Things]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Duffer Bros. Netflix Supernatural Drama Series Sets Young Cast, Gets Title|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/duffer-bros-netflix-series-stranger-things-young-cast-1201502552|accessdate=3 September 2015|magazine=Deadline.com|date=20 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Spangler|first1=Todd|title=Netflix Casts 7 Young Actors in ''Stranger Things'' Supernatural Drama from Duffer Brothers|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-stranger-things-duffer-brothers-winona-ryder-1201574835|accessdate=28 August 2016|website=Variety|date=20 August 2015}}</ref> In 2016, he starred in the movie ''[[As You Are (film)|As You Are]]''.\n\nIn May 2017, Heaton was cast to star as [[Cannonball (comics)|Samuel \"Sam\" Guthrie / Cannonball]] in ''[[New Mutants (film)|New Mutants]]'', a 2020 film based on the [[Marvel Comics]] comic book of the [[New Mutants|same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/new-mutants-movie-cannonball-charlie-heaton/|title='New Mutants' Finds Its Cannonball with 'Stranger Things' Star Charlie Heaton|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|work=Collider|date=31 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> In August 2018, the BBC announced that Heaton would be playing [[Joseph Merrick]], commonly known as the \"Elephant Man\", in a new two-part drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/the-elephant-man|title=Charlie Heaton is The Elephant Man|publisher=BBC|date=22 August 2019|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> The casting drew criticism from a disability charity group, the group's head saying that not using a disabled actor was a missed opportunity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/anger-over-casting-of-stranger-things-star-charlie-heaton-as-elephant-man-11485440|title=Anger over casting of Stranger Things star Charlie Heaton as Elephant Mann|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has a son, Archie (born 2014), with his ex-girlfriend Akiko Matsuura [1]. Since 2016, he has been in a relationship with his ''Stranger Things'' co-star, [[Natalia Dyer]], who plays Jonathan's girlfriend [[Nancy Wheeler]] on the show.<ref>https://www.capitalfm.com/news/tv-film/stranger-things/natalia-dyer-charlie-heaton-relationship-timeline/</ref>\n\nHeaton missed the premiere of ''Stranger Things 2'' as on 21 October 2017. Heaton was detained at Los Angeles International Airport in October due to possession of trace amounts of cocaine, reports had said. He was not arrested and immediately returned to London. More than a week later, he said in a statement that his planned travel to the U.S. was \"affected by an issue at U.S. immigration\" and that he \"was not arrested or charged with a crime.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/919917/stranger-things-charlie-heaton-opens-up-about-cocaine-possession-reports|title=Charlie Heaton Opens Up About Cocaine Possession Reports|last=|first=|date=2018-03-11|website=E! Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film==